<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> JET Announce Breakthrough in Nuclear Fusion Performance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at the Joint European
Torus (JET) announced here today they had created new world
records again in imitating the energy-producing process of the
Sun. The breakthrough will make it possible for mankind to harness
a safe, clean and endless source of energy.
</P>
<P>
JET broke the world record for power fusion on October 31, by
using the deuterium-tritium fuel mixture. The power output peaked
at 16.1 megawatts, said Tom Elsworth, who is in charge of public
relations at JET.
</P>
<P>
It also broke the world record for the ratio of fusion power
produced to the net input power with 0.65 in the same experiment.
</P>
<P>
"Almost the same results were obtained twice within two hours,
that means the experiment can be repeated," he added.
</P>
<P>
The former record was created by JET on September 22 when
output power peaked at 12.9 megawatts and the ratio of fusion
power produced to the net input power was 0.6.
</P>
<P>
If the ratio is above 1, the fusion will not only be maintained
by the energy it releases, but also output net energy.
</P>
<P>
In November 1991, for the first time, controlled fusion power
was produced by JET with output power peaking at 1.7 megawatts. In
November, 1994, the U.S. Tokamak Fusion Test Reactor has produced
10.7 megawatts of fusion power at a ratio of 0.28.
</P>
<P>
JET, based at Abingdon, Oxfordshire, Britain, is seen as the
largest and most successful fusion experiment in the
world. Construction began in 1978 and the project has been
operational since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
