<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, November 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's two main opposition parties, the
National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and the United Liberal
Democrats (ULD), on Monday officially confirmed NCNP's leader Kim
Dae-jung as their joint candidate for the December presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony held at the parliamentary hall in downtown Seoul,
Kim Dae-jung and ULD leader Kim Jong-pil signed an agreement on
fielding Kim Dae-jung as the single presidential candidate between
the two parties. (SKorea-Opposition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- The newly sworn-in President of the Republic of
Congo Denis Sassou Nguesso named a 33-member government on Monday
in the capital Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Martin Mberi, one of the leading former allies of ousted
President Pascal Lissouba who split with him over the four-month
civil war against Sassou, was the new transport minister.
</P>
<P>
Sassou has said he will collaborate with all those who disavow
Lissouba. (Cameroun-New Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- New Zealand Prime Minister Jim Bolger announced
Sunday night that he will step down at the end of the month as
prime minister, Radio NZ reported Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
He announced that Minister of State-owned Enterprises Jenny
Shipley told him that she had enough support from the National
Party MPs to challenge his leadership at the National Caucus
meeting Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Bolger said he will step down after attending the APEC meeting
in Vancouver and paying a visit to China. (New Zealand-Prime
Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh announced
here Monday evening that he will resign.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made the announcement to reporters before he meets his
economic ministers Monday evening at the residence of Chatichai
Choonhavan, chief economic advisor of the government and leader of
the second largest ruling party Chart Pattana Party (CPP), to
discuss the current economic situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said that he had done his best in solving the
country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that he will make a formal announcement
of resignation on Thursday. (Thailand-PM-Resign-3rdlead)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
fixed the meeting with United States President Bill Clinton during
his visit next week, Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Clinton summit was once in doubt because of the
reported Clinton's displeasure with Netanyahu's handling of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, which was resumed early last
month after a seven-month freeze thanks to the intensive
U.S. mediation. (Israel-US-Netanyahu-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- President Kim Young-sam's second son Kim Hyun-chul was
released on bail Monday after spending five and half months in
jail.
</P>
<P>
Kim was sentenced to three years in jail by Seoul District
Court on October 13 convicted of evading taxes and peddling
influence in exchanges for money from businessmen.
</P>
<P>
In its ruling on Kim's appeal for bail, the Seoul high court
said Monday that according to the principle of criminal suit, Kim
should undergo trial without physical detention. (SKorea-Kim
Hyun-chul-Release)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- More than 1,000 Chinese scientists, businessmen
and visiting scholars in southern California on Sunday hailed the
visit to the United States by Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon hosted in honor of Jiang, who is winding up his
9-day state visit to the United States, representatives of the
overseas Chinese said that Jiang's visit is a great event in both
China-U.S. relations and in the cause of peace and development in
the world. (US-Jiang's Visit) 
</P>
