<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Deems Washington Talks Decisive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) termed today's talks in
Washington between the Palestinians and Israelis as decisive as
they will help outline stances of all parties.
</P>
<P>
PLO chief delegate Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy will head their delegations at the
talks sponsored by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in
the U.S. capital today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview granted Monday morning to the Cairo-based Voice
of Arabs radio, Zakaria al Agha, a member of the PLO Executive
Committee, pointed out that the three sides have agreed on an
agenda that includes issues of redeployment, unilateral measures,
security matters as well as final phase negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that the U.S., as the main peace sponsor, will
honor its commitments towards the peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hassan Asfour, director of the Palestinian
Negotiations Department, expressed pessimism over the Washington
talks.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Israeli government of "wasting time," saying
that the Israeli delegation is not authorized to adopt resolutions
regarding basic issues such as settlement and redeployment.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations should depend on what had
been agreed upon in the first round of talks held in the
U.S. under Albright, otherwise they will become a mere waste of
time," he told Monte Carlo radio.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-backed meetings, the second round of high-level talks
in seven months of Palestinian-Israeli standoff, was postponed
from October 27 until today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been at odds over Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's proposal to move straight into accelerated
"final status" talks that will tackle more difficult issues like
the future of settlements and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel first implement
long-delayed withdrawal of Israeli troops in most rural areas of
the West Bank and agree on a freeze in settlement activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
