<HEADLINE> Shevardnadze Defends Role of CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze today defended the role of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS), saying the existence of the CIS is
important for developing regional cooperation and safeguarding
member countries' independence.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the national radio in the capital,
Tbilisi, Shevardnadze dismissed the idea that the CIS is useless
and Georgia should quit it.
</P>
<P>
The CIS explores great geopolitical potential for wide-ranging
cooperation between the member states, Itar-Tass News Agency
quoted Shevardnadze as saying.
</P>
<P>
The body was conducive to member countries' efforts in
protecting and consolidating their independence, territorial
integrity and maintaining national stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the close relations between Georgia and Ukraine,
Shevardnadze said the strategic alliance of the two states is
aimed at enhancing the CIS, and it had proved a successful attempt
in bringing out the CIS' potential.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze also noted the key role of Russia in the CIS. "It
is doubtless that Russia has a special place in the CIS and the
fate of the CIS hinges greatly on Russia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
