<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies Preventing UN Team from Doing Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Minister of Culture and
Information Hammam Abdul-Khalek today denied that his country
prevented U.N. arms inspection teams from doing their work, Iraq
News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in an apparent bid to defuse the tension
between Iraq and the U.N. caused by Iraqi blocking of an American
inspector from entering an inspection site this morning.
</P>
<P>
The missile team that included an American, and two other U.N.
inspection groups sent out this morning were called back to
headquarters after the incident.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Khalek explained that the Iraqi authorities told the team
members that the American should stay out while the other members
could get into the site and do their work.
</P>
<P>
"The first team of the U.N. arms inspectors decided not to get
in and returned to their headquarters. The other teams turned back
before they got to the sites because they got relevant notice from
their headquarters in Baghdad," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister said that the U.N. arms inspection teams
could fulfill their duties according to schedule and within the
framework agreed upon with the Iraqi authorities. Only Americans
working in the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraqi mass destruction weapons are barred from working
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. sources here, the UNSCOM decided today to
suspend its activities in Iraq in view of the fact that its
American members were not allowed to participate in the inspection.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi ruling Revolutionary Command Council issued a
statement on October 29 demanding all Americans working in the
U.N. weapons inspection teams to leave Iraq within a week.
</P>
<P>
The move was to protest against a U.N. Security Council
resolution threatening a travel ban on some of Iraqi officials if
the Baghdad government continued to block U.N. inspectors' work.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly accused the Americans in the U.N. teams of
conducting espionage and trying to delay the lifting of the
economic sanctions against now in its seventh year.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iraq again refused the entry into its territory of
the three American weapons inspectors it turned away earlier on
Thursday, despite U.S. warning of serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
The United States has not ruled out military action to force
Baghdad into compliance, although force is opposed by Russia,
France and a number of Arab states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
