<HEADLINE> Official: Peace Treaty Not Mean Kurils Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia will not necessarily lose
its sovereignty over the Kuril islands, even if it reaches an
agreement with Japan to sign a peace treaty by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Mitrofanov, chairman of the committee for geopolitics in
Russia's State Duma, made this point to the Itar-Tass news agency
today.
</P>
<P>
It was necessary for the two countries to discuss the Kurils
problem and the signing of a peace treaty. But no time limits
should be set for such talks, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia should not hurry to make decisions pertaining to its
inner interests since it might cause irretrievable damage to its
national security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Differences between Russia and Japan would be settled by
creating a financial and business center in the Kurils, which
aimed at promoting economic development of the region on a
mutually beneficial basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
During their two-day informal meeting which started on
Saturday, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed to sign a peace treaty and
partly resolve territorial and other problems between the two
countries by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
