<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Outlines Britain's EU Presidency Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook outlined the priorities of Britain's European Union (EU)
presidency in Dubin early today, saying "Give Europe back to the
people" is its main mission.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Institute for European Affairs in Dublin, Cook
said that the agenda of Britain's EU presidency in the first half
of next year would be based on "the concerns of the peoples of
Europe."
</P>
<P>
Cook, who is on a brief visit to Ireland, stressed that
unemployment, the main headache haunting all the EU countries,
would be at the top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
On the crucial single European currency, due to be launched on
January 1 1999, Cook said: "Even though we will not be taking part
in the first wave in 1999, it is still in our interest that it
should succeed."
</P>
<P>
"We will use our presidency to ensure that those countries who
wish to form a single currency can get off to the best possible
start," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook also said the Labor government wanted to press ahead with
planned talks on enlarging the 15-nation bloc, adding that the
negotiations should start with the states best prepared for
membership.
</P>
<P>
"Opening talks with those who are still not ready would raise
hopes unfairly. It would soon leave them disappointed and
disillusioned," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Britain (will) help those who have further to travel, to make
sure they are not being rejected. The enlargement process must be
like a pipeline," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary pointed out that the other major tasks
during Britain's presidency would be fighting crime, drugs and
protecting the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
