<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Calls for New Page in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CRETE, GREECE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis today urged the Balkans to have a "new reality" and
a "new page" in order to avoid a return to "old practices," which
he warned would lead to the region's "defeat".
</P>
<P>
"we are at a crossroads, and persistence in old practices or a
return to the past would lead all of us to defeat," he said while
addressing the opening ceremony of the first-ever Balkan summit
here.
</P>
<P>
The Balkan region was regarded as a "region of bloody clashes
and conflicts," he said, adding that such a situation should be
changed.
</P>
<P>
With the globalization of the economy, economic frontiers had
been been abolished and groupings of states such as the European
Union (EU) and the World Trade Organization (PTO) were being
formed, he said. "These historic changes demand adaptation and
redetermination of policies for the coming century," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Simitis called for "seeking new perspectives on all the crucial
issues."
</P>
<P>
The Balkan countries all desired an answer to the problems that
separate them, ha said, adding that solutions could not be sought
on the basis of the rivalries of the past decades.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the consolidation of peace, respect of
international law, economic cooperation and solidarity in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Leaders and representatives of Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria,
Greece, Romania, Macedonia, Turkey and Yugoslavia are attending
the two-day summit aimed at seeking ways to settle their political
differences and expand cooperations in all fields, especially in
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
