<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Recommend Ways for Treatment of Heart Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Health experts have recommended
guidelines to prevent and treat cardiovascular diseases, paving
the way for a more effective treatment of millions of patients
suffering form thrombotic disorders, according to a press release
issued here today by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held in Geneva on October 27-31 by the WHO Expert
Committee on Biological Standardization, the experts adopted a new
set of guidelines for oral anticoagulants, a class of drugs
inhibiting blood clotting.
</P>
<P>
These drugs cannot be prescribed at a fixed dose. For each
patient the dose must be adjusted according to the result of a
vitally important blood clotting test to be conducted every four
weeks. If the dose is low the patient is at risk of developing
thrombosis. If the dose is high the patient is at risk of
spontaneous bleeding.
</P>
<P>
The new test requires the use of laboratory reagents called
thromboplastins which are commercial products producing different
clotting times for a particular blood sample. In the past, all too
often, patients going to different hospitals were given different
prescriptions depending on the type of thromboplastins used by the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Patients suffering from thrombotic disorders have clots of
coagulated blood that forms within a blood vessel or inside the
heart and remains at the site of its formation, often impeding the
flow of blood.
</P>
<P>
For the most part, the thrombotic disorders are linked to
circulatory diseases, such as heart attack and stroke, which
account for at least 15 million deaths every year. Many millions
more are disabled by them. The costs of caring for patients with
circulatory diseases account for about 10 percent of direct health
care costs in developed countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Oil Exports to S. Africa Remain Stable: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi said today that Iranian export of crude oil
to South Africa remain stable.
</P>
<P>
He said it was not accurate when some reports said that Iranian
crude oil exports to South Africa had fallen by about 12 million
barrels last year while those from Saudi Arabia rose to about 16
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, I don't think there has been a decrease. We have very
good relations in terms of oil sales to South Africa. I don't think
there will be drastic change in the amount of business we have with
South Africa," Kharrazi told reporters after meeting his South African
counterpart Alfred Nzo in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi, who arrived here for the second sitting of the joint
commission of Iran and South Africa, said there was a strong political
will in South Africa and Iran to enhance their economic relations.
</P>
<P>
"What remains is for us to promote trade relations between our two
countries," Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
Iran is South Africa's main source of crude oil, but the
latter has increasingly looked at other markets, informed sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Petroleum Industry Association has said that
Iranian crude oil exports to South Africa fell to 68.2 million barrels
in 1996 from 80.7 million barrels in 1995. Crude from Kuwait rose to
20.9 million barrels from 4.2 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a stalled oil storage agreement which gives Iran
access to strategic facilities at Saldanha Bay in the Western Cape
Province, Kharrazi said Iran was at present not interest in making use
of South Africa's oil storage facilities at Saldanha Bay.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we don't think there is such a need, " he said, saying
that Iran had a strong shipping line to move its oil to end-users,
removing the need for a storage facility along the way.
</P>
<P>
The idea of Iran storing about 15 million barrels of oil at
Saldanha north of Cape Town was raised in 1995. Although no agreement
on the matter has been signed, a study on the environmental impact of
such a move was commissioned.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi was likely to discuss the matter with South African
Minister of of Energy and Minerals Penuell Manduna tomorrow, Foreign
Minister Nzo said today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
