<HEADLINE> UN to Try New Strategy in Afghan Mediation: Holl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. is considering
changing its strategy in brokering peace in Afghanistan by
shifting the focus from the Afghan warring factions to the
regional countries with influence upon the country, U.N. Special
Envoy to Afghanistan Norbert Holl said today.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Secretary General is preparing for a peace conference
which will involve a very small number of countries of influence
in Afghanistan", Holl told Xinhua in an exclusive interview at the
United Nations Special Mission to Afghanistan (UNSMA) based in the
Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
The UNSMA has been focusing its attention on mediating between
the Afghans during the past five years, but the lack of comprise
among all Afghan parties has rendered this method fruitless so
far, the UN envoy said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the U.N. is trying a new method, he said. "If we
cannot do it from inside, let's try from the outside," he added.
</P>
<P>
The countries with influence has not yet in the past seriously
discussed with the U.N. mission how to solve the Afghanistan
dilemma, but the U.N. is now trying to build a more solid, a more
reliable and a more open cooperative relationship with these
countries, Holl said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that foreign interference, which has always been
existing, is another major reason for the continuation of war in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Holl stressed the important position of Iran and Pakistan in
the peace-finding process in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned the importance of Central Asian republics and
other regional countries which have great influence in the
political arena of the world.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the peace conference is not an easy thing, Holl
said that the preparatory work must be very careful and therefore
takes long to ensure a final success.
</P>
<P>
Holl, who resumed his office last July, has submitted
resignation to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan. He will leave
here at the end of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
