<HEADLINE> French Trucking Labor Conflict Sides to Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The two labor conflict sides of
France's trucking transport industry will resume talks on Tuesday,
after lorry drivers set up hundreds of barriers to block highways
across the country to push for a raise of salary.
</P>
<P>
Jehan de Marne, the president of the main organization of
owners of trucking companies in France UFT said that he was
favorable in principle to return to the table of negotiations,
after quitting it early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
UFT could sign a compromise agreement with the union
representatives this time, said UNOSTRA, the union of owners of
smaller trucking companies.
</P>
<P>
The UFT quit the negotiation table in the early morning of
Sunday after refusing to sign a text agreeing to a 20 percent
raise of salary of truckers before the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
But the main trade union participating in the strike, the Force
Ouvriere (FO), said that the renewed talks should be more
conformed to the "reality in the field to the requests of the
employees on strike."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the blockade of highways by the lorry drivers has
raised concern and criticism in France and abroad, and raised
panic in a number of neighboring countries, after it reminded one
of last year's paralysis caused by a 12-day blockade by the
truckers.
</P>
<P>
One lorry driver was wounded today by a striker at a blockade
in Villefranche-sur-Saone on a highway linking Lyon with Paris.
</P>
<P>
France's national employers' organization CNPF said in a
communique today that the strike is weakening the economic
resumption of France and are hurting several economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Spanish lorry drivers waged a protest against the strike today
in Villefranche-sur-Saone in the Rhone in southern France, to show
their refusal to become the "hostage" of the French lorry drivers.
</P>
<P>
Spanish lorry drivers also forced open a blockage on a highway
between Lyon and Paris today.
</P>
<P>
Angry French lorry drivers today seized several roads in the
port area of the northern city of Rouen, while about 170 barriers
were counted on the highways across France by mid-day today.
</P>
<P>
Some oil storages and refinery factories were also blocked
today by lorry drivers, while the country's petroleum industry
union, UFIP, protested the move.
</P>
<P>
"We perfectly understand that the truckers use their right of
strike, which is constitutional and legitimate. But blocking the
roads and the oil storages is an act of another nature which can
have very grave repercussions on the daily life of all and on
enterprises," said Bernard Calvet, president of UFIP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
