<HEADLINE> France Asks U.N. Security Council to Make </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- France today asked the United
Nations Security Council to take decisions on Iraq after Baghdad
challenged the U.N. in the field of investigation of its
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"We once again regret profoundly this incident which makes up a
factor of aggravation of the crisis," said French Foreign Ministry
spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said, when referring to Iraq's
decision to expel two American experts from the team of U.N.
special commission in charge of disarmament in Iraq (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
He said that France remained determined to do all it can to
push Iraq to cooperate with the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the U.N. Security Council to examine in which
measure the resolutions which it has adopted are respected (by
Iraq)... It is also up to it to take, in the light of the facts
which it is related to, the decisions imposed by the circumstances
and by the preservation of its authority," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein today proposed holding dialogue
with the U.N. over its disarmament and suggested receiving an
American envoy in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
This proposal has been rejected by Washington. 
</P>
