<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan`s Public Sector Doctors Ends Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Health professionals employed in
Jordan`s public sector today ended a three-day strike but failed
to press the government to give them 60 percent share of the
revenues collected from rich patients.
</P>
<P>
However, the organizers will discuss new actions and will
possibly resume strike next Monday, said Raef Faris, a member of
the executive council of the Jordan Medical Association (JMA).
</P>
<P>
The strike across the country involved 22 public hospitals and
650 health centers, and organizations such as JMA, Jordan Dentist
Association, Jordan Pharmacist Association and Jordan Doctors
Association.
</P>
<P>
In the kingdom, the poor people and government employees can be
treated free of charge in public hospitals and health centers. The
rich patients pay an estimated annual treatment fee of 37 million
Jordanian dinars (about 52 million U.S. dollars), with revenues
reaching 7 million dinars (about 10 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health promised in a 1996 agreement with JMA to
give 60 percent of annual revenues to the health professionals.
But it lowered the percentage to 36 on the ground that money was
needed to cover operational costs of the hospitals and health
center, prompting the nationwide strike.
</P>
<P>
The first revenue-sharing agreement was signed between the JMA
and the ministry in 1992. It was stipulated then that health
professionals could get 50 percent of the revenues collected from
rich patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Europe's Economy Forecast to Grow 1.7% in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Economies of the countries of
eastern Europe, the Baltics and the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) are expected to grow by 1.7 percent in 1997 as a
whole, the first time since the region began the shift to market
economies seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
(EBRD) said in its annual health check on the region's economies
that after years of contraction, the overall output is only 70
percent of its 1989 level.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that continued progress in structural reform has
been made in most countries of the region, but there are great
disparities in the transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Those countries which have reformed more vigorously have
recovered from recession more rapidly and attracted greater
private capital inflows, said the bank's 1997 Transition Report.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the region's turn-around in output is the
recovery from recession of the area's largest economy the Russian
economy, which is predicted to show "cautious but positive" growth
of about one percent.
</P>
<P>
The economies of 11 of the 25 countries are set to grow by more
than four percent while six of them are still showing falling
output, with the economies of Turkmenistan and Albania forecast to
contract this year by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that investment in the region has increased
over the past two years and is expected to top 55 billion U.S.
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank pointed out that corruption remains a major
disincentive to investors, particularly in the CIS. Income
inequality and poverty have also increased throughout the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Claim 12 More Lives in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people, eight
of whom children, have died in the floods which hit Bardhere
district of Gedo region as heavy rains continue to cause
fatalities in human lives and animals in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the police commander of the town, Gurhan Hirsi
Ali, the floods came after the town has experienced one of its
heaviest rains for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the heavy rains has continued for 14 days, with the
floods and the destruction emerging in the last seven days.
</P>
<P>
The police commander who spoke with the journalists via radio
in Bardhere said the rain waters alone could not affect the town
much, but the disaster started when Jubba River crushed its banks
and over flew its nearby residential areas.
</P>
<P>
"As many as 250 houses were destroyed by the floods which also
divided the town into two parts," said Ali.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people are believed to have died in the regions
of Gedo, Bay Bakol, Kiwer and Middle Jubba in the past three
weeks since the heavy rains and floods began.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of animals, mainly cattle and goats, were also
washed away by the waters, and dozens of villages and towns which
remain isolated by flood that cut off the roads linking them to
the other towns.
</P>
<P>
In the capital, Mogadishu, rains have been falling heavily,
fortunately with no fatalities reported.
</P>
<P>
However, the commodities such as the coal, meat, vegetables
and imported food items have increased in price sharply in
Mogadishu owing to mal-communication resulted from the waters.
</P>
</TEXT>
