<HEADLINE> Cyprus Hopes for Improved Greece-Turkey Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus believes an improvement
in the relations between Greece and Turkey will positively reflect
on Cyprus, a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Manolis Christofides said at his daily press briefing that
today's meeting on the Greek island Crete between Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis and his Turkish counterpart Mesut Yilmaz
will open a "window of hope" for Cyprus, like their Madrid meeting
last July.
</P>
<P>
Simitis and Yilmaz are due to meet during a two-day summit of
Balkan leaders that began Monday in Crete.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of last July's Madrid summit of North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), the two premiers agreed to ease
tensions in the Aegean, where the two countries have almost come
to blows over sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward and hope that an improvement in the relations
between Greece and Turkey will be achieved as this will also
reflect on Cyprus," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops landed
and took over the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies and guarantors of Cyprus'
independence under a 1960 treaty, have long been at adds over
this eastern Mediterranean strategic island.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Simitis will raise the Cyprus problem to Yilmaz,
the spokesman said "we know that in every meeting with Turkish
officials, Simitis puts on the top of agenda Greece's views
regarding the promotion of a Cyprus solution."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leaders and representatives of six Greek Cypriot
and four Turkish Cypriot political parties met today at the
U.N.-controlled Ledra Palace Hotel in Nicosia to exchange views
on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique, issued at the end of the meeting, says that
they hope that the meeting between the prime ministers of Greece
and Turkey, in Crete, will be successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
