<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Denounces Turkish Maneuvers in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
denounced the presence of Turkish naval vessels and military
aircraft in Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern Cyprus as
provocations.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 warplanes and warships, along with some
Turkish military units, are reported to take part in military
exercises "Taurus" in northern Cyprus, which started today, and
"Determination" in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn these exercises and we consider them a show
of strength as well as a display of unwillingness to respect
international law and order," government spokesman Manolis
Christofides said here today at his daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The use of F-16 fighters in mock air-raids in the Republic's
air-space proves that the Cypriot government's decision to buy
anti-aircraft missiles was right, Christofides added.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government decided early this year to buy
Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air missiles, scheduled for
deployment in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has responsed with threats that it will launch
preemptive strike if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military exercises took place amid tensions
between Turkey and Greece following a Greek and Cypriot joint
military exercise last month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here today, U.N. Resident Representative
in Cyprus Gustave Feissel reiterated U.N. and Security Council
concern with the situation in Cyprus and reminded of resolutions
calling for a reduction of troops and a freeze in the military
build-up.
</P>
<P>
Feissel pointed out that "unfortunately until now this has not
been heeded by anybody" and said that if the situation remains as
it is today it has the potential of worsening and creating
tensions.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about all kinds of military exercises and
I think it would be much better if none take place because
it would certainly not help in creating the right kind of
climate and reducing tensions," Feissel said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
