<HEADLINE> Health Disaster Early Warning System Urged to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- An expert in the Addis
Ababa University today urged for the immediate establishment of
an early warning system for health disasters such as epidemics in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a training course here, the expert, Derege Kebede,
an associate professor and Chairman of the Department of
Community Health at the university, said although fairly
effective early warning system has been developed for disasters
related to drought and famine, similar shemes for health
disasters have not so far been launched in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, he said, epidemics are claiming the lives of
millions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in a move to curb the spread of epidemics, his
department is making utmost efforts to train medical doctors
and public health practitioners in early warning system of health
disasters.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks to the training course, delegation head
of the International Committee of the Red Cross in Ethiopia,
Georges Comininos said the fact that the course is taking place
in Ethiopia has a symbolic significance for the country has been
severly affected in its recent history by large scale of health
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The 18-day help course is being attended by 30 health
professional s drawn from 28 countries across the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
