<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: A New Chapter in China-U.S. Relations (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin left here for home today after winding up his nine-day state
visit to the United States, which took him to seven U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Jiang held talks with U.S. President Bill
Clinton, met with U.S. congressmen and other senior government
officials, and had broad contacts with leaders in U.S. business,
commerce and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The successful visit has opened a new chapter in
China-U.S. relations. It has achieved its objectives of deepening
understanding, broadening common ground, promoting cooperation and
building a future together.
</P>
<P>
This is the first official visit by a Chinese head of state to
the United States in 12 years and the most important one paid by
Chinese leaders since Comrade Deng Xiaoping's 1979 America tour.
</P>
<P>
This historic visit shows that China-U.S. relations have
entered a new period of development. It is of great practical and
historical significance in promoting world peace and development
and in seeking a peaceful and stable international environment for
our country's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have attached great significance to the visit,
which attracted close attention and won positive comments from the
whole international community.
</P>
<P>
The most important achievement of Jiang's fruitful visit is
that both sides, drawing lessons from the past and setting eyes on
the future, have reached a common understanding on developing
21st century-oriented China-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two sides issued a joint statement,
announcing that the two countries will work to build a
constructive strategic partnership geared toward the next
century.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed that the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques
are the basic principles for developing bilateral relations, which
should be viewed and handled from the global and historical
perspectives of strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
The converging points in their common interests should be
sought and differences be resolved on the basis of mutual respect,
consultation on an equal footing and seeking common ground while
reserving differences. This has clearly defined the direction for
a healthy and stable China-U.S. relationship geared toward the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
This visit has enabled both sides to be more aware of their
broad common interests in safeguarding world and regional peace
and stability, promoting the development of global economy,
pushing forward the regional cooperation in the Asia-Pacific and
finding solutions to transnational issues of international concern.
</P>
<P>
They are more aware of the great potential in further
strengthening cooperation in bilateral trade, environment, energy,
and science and technology. All these constitute the strategic
basis of China-U.S. relations in the new situation.
</P>
<P>
In order to establish the constructive strategic partnership
geared toward the 21st century, both sides have decided on
exchanges of visits by presidents of the two countries on a
regular basis, setting up direct communications links between
them, and increasing exchanges of regular visits by officials at
the ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they held consultations on energy, environment
protection, economy and trade, peaceful utilization of nuclear
energy, nonproliferation of weapons of mass destruction, human
rights, law, relations between the two militaries, education as
well as cultural exchanges. They have reached agreements on
concrete measures and steps of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Another important achievement of Jiang's visit is the deepening
of mutual understanding between the two peoples through increased
contacts. During his visit, President Jiang attended more than 40
functions and gave more than 30 addresses including a series of
important speeches. He elaborated on China's stand and policies in
developing China-U.S. relations. He briefed the audiences on
China's achievements in its reform and opening up as well as its
modernization drive, and on the fine historical and cultural
traditions of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The contacts have helped the American public to learn more
about China from different perspectives, thus giving fresh impetus
to developing bilateral relations, enhancing trust and promoting
cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: A New Chapter in China-U.S. Relations (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang's visit helped further expand trade and economic
cooperation between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
During his nine-day visit, the Chinese president met more than
100 leading U.S. entrepreneurs and businessmen. He toured
high-tech companies including IBM, AT&AMP;T, the Bell Lab. and the
Hughes Electronics Corporation and visited the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States signed important documents on
cooperation in energy, environment and the peaceful use of nuclear
technology. In addition, a Chinese trade delegation, arriving in
the United States a few days before Jiang's visit, signed with
U.S. companies contracts worth billions of dollars, which cover
projects in aviation, petrochemical and power industries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's visit showed that Chinese and U.S. economies are highly
complementary and stand to benefit from the great potentials of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Noting that they had reached agreement on many major
international and bilateral issues, Jiang and Clinton admitted
frankly that differences remain on issues like human rights and
trade.
</P>
<P>
The development of China-U.S. relations, suffering unexpected
twists and turns, especially after the end of the Cold War, had
undergone a tortuous course. It is impossible for the two sides
to resolve all their differences overnight.
</P>
<P>
The success of Jiang's visit demonstrated that different social
systems, values and cultural traditions should be no barriers to
the development of state-to-state friendly cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Dialogue is always better than confrontation; engagement better
than containment; cooperation better than sanctions and exchanges
better than isolation.
</P>
<P>
To this end, it is of crucial importance to adopt a strategic
perspective, to grasp historic opportunities, to be good at
seeking common interests and to handle differences or
contradictions with a sensible and calm attitude.
</P>
<P>
When visiting the United States in 1979, Deng Xiaoping said the
Pacific Ocean should never be a barrier that separates China and
the United States, but a link that binds the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the historic moment of the turn of the century, President
Jiang again crossed the Pacific Ocean to strengthen the ties of
friendly cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
To maintain a healthy and stable relationship between China and
the United States is not only in the basic interests of the two
peoples, but also conducive to world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
While making efforts to improve relations with the United
States, China will continue to enhance contacts with other powers
and promote cooperation with developing countries, so as to
contribute to bringing a peaceful, stable and prosperous world
into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
