<HEADLINE> Ghana's Accra Airport Safe Despite Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The international airport in
Accra, capital of Ghana, is safe and remains open despite the
strike of air traffic controllers, according to the Ghana Civil
Aviation Authority (GCAA).
</P>
<P>
"Senior air traffic controllers and instructors are manning the air
control system pending the amicable settlement of the impasse," GCAA
director-general wing commander Andy Mensah said in a statement
released late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that flight coordination has already been
established with all adjacent air control centers in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
Air controllers closed the country's airspace Sunday morning for
pay increase and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
They shut down the main control tower in the airport and informed
the airlines that the Accra information region had been closed.
</P>
<P>
The GCAA director-general had to string together a contigent of
control crew called from among senior management personnel, the Ghana
Airways and retired air control staff before he announced the airspace
was open.
</P>
<P>
The strikers have warned that the safety of aircraft could not be
guaranteed as those manning air traffic control were unqualified.
</P>
<P>
The situation, if continued, could affect air traffic within, to
and from Ghana, Togo and Benin because Ghana is the nerve center of
the major air traffic system covering the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
