<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Ready to Exchange Information on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides has expressed the Greek Cypriot side's willingness to
exchange informations on the location of graves of people from
island's two rival communities listed as missing persons.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by U.N. Resident Representative
Gustave Feissel after a meeting with President Clerides during
which they discussed the latest development on Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Feissel told reporters that "I received a letter from Clerides
saying that he was now ready to exchange that information on his
side."
</P>
<P>
President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash met
here in July and agreed to provide each other immediately and
simultaneously all informations already at their disposal on the
location of graves of Greek and Turkish Cypriots missing.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of information was scheduled to take place by the
end of last September, as a first step in resolving this humanitarian
issue.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1619 Greek Cypriots were listed as missing persons
soon after the 1974 Turkish invasion, while the Turkish Cypriot
side said there were around 500 Turkish Cypriots missing since
the intercommunal clashes that broke out in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Feissel expressed the hope that the information would be
exchanged very soon.
</P>
<P>
On his meeting with the President, Feissel said they discussed
a proposed visit to the island by the U.N. Secretary-General's
special advisor on Cyprus, Diego Cordovez scheduled for November
18.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan wrote to the two sides in Cyprus, as well as the
governments of Greece and Turkey, proposing a visit by Cordovez
to investigate whether they would be willing to participate in
open-ended talks to solve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez chaired two rounds of Cyprus peace talks this Summer,
in the U.S. and Switzerland, which reached a deadlock because
Denktash refused to negotiate unless the European Union withholds
its decision for accession talks with Cyprus next Spring.
</P>
<P>
Feissel refrained from commenting on what could be expected
from Cordovez's visit in view of Denktash's public statements
that he would not be able to meet the U.N. envoy in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader, who is now in the U.S. for
meetings on the Cyprus issue, said he would be in Turkey for
medical examinations on November 18 when the U.N. advisor is
expected to visit the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey landed its troops and took over
the northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
