<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar President Calls for Cooperation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 3 (xinhua) -- Zanzibar President Salmin
Amour today called on African police forces to join hands in combating
misuse of arms in the continent.
</P>
<P>
He told a five-day African regional workshop on arms regulations
here that co-operation was necessary because arms offenses were often
of transitional nature and no single country could effectively
control them.
</P>
<P>
Amour cited examples of misuse of arms as armed robberies and
plane hijackings, most of which result in loss of lives and
destruction of property.
</P>
<P>
He said there was urgent need for controlling the supply of
arms and checking their misuse to ensure that peace and security
was not threatened in the region.
</P>
<P>
"I hope during your deliberations you will come up with strong and
clear resolutions on what should be done to check the widespread
misuse of arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Inspector General of Police, Omar Mahita, told
the 53 delegates that although there were elaborate laws governing the
importation and use of civilian arms, some people still smuggled arms
into their countries, threatening peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Mahita called for international co-operation through devising
common strategies on fighting the smugglers who often beat the
law enforcers.
</P>
<P>
An official from the United Nations Office in Vienna, Slowomir
Redo, underscored the importance of regular communication among
the African countries as a strategy in fighting the misuse.
</P>
<P>
He said the experience and knowledge from the workshop would assist
all UN member states in effectively fighting the problem which is a
menace to peace and stability in the world.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, sponsored by the UN Crime Prevention and Criminal
Justice Division in Vienna, draws participation of senior police
officers from the whole Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
