<HEADLINE> Zambia Searching for Phosphate Fertilizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will investigate
into mine dump waste throughout the country in a bid to find out
whether the waste contain any minerals which can be utilized for
agricultural purposes, Mine and Minerals Development Minister Christon
Tembo said here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening an international conference on phosphate resources and
food security in Africa, Christon Tembo said that in order to increase food
production on the African continent there is need for the improvement
of soil fertility and sustainable agricultural practice.
</P>
<P>
He said many African countries especially those in sub-Saharan
Africa suffer from phosphorus deficiency which is one of the
contributing factors to the decline in food production.
</P>
<P>
While Africa has numerous mineral deposits scattered throughout the
continent which remain unexploited, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fertilizer imports on the continent are a great drain of the
scarce foreign exchange despite boasting of many phosphate deposits in
the region, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem of low quality deposits can be overcomed by
producing cheaper forms of phosphate fertilizers in which a portion of
the phosphate content is converted to water soluble and can be used
immediately by plants.
</P>
<P>
The utilization of this important plant nutrient could have a
positive impact on food and crop production in Africa because the
benefit could lead to economical empowerment of farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, acting United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) resident representative, Omoefe Oyaide, said UNDP is keen to
explore every opportunity to enhance the development of the economy
particularly the rural sector which is dominated by a large number of
small-scale farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said 40 percent of UNDP support in the next five years will go
to developing agriculture, rural development and food security.
</P>
</TEXT>
