<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official: Mistrust Mars Talks with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief delegate to the
Arab League (AL) Mohamad Sobeih said here today that the peace
talks with Israel in Washington is marred by "much caution and
many doubts."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Middle East News Agency, he said that
the Palestinian side continues to feel bitter about previous
experience with Israel as PLO chief delegate Mahmoud Abbas and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy is having talks today in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
"This round of talks was delayed to give Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy authorization from Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and the Israeli mini-Cabinet in order to avoid
a setback in the talks as was the case on previous occasions,"
Sobeih said.
</P>
<P>
During previous talks, Levy displayed "ill-fitting optimism"
and failed to carry out promises he made at the previous round of
talks in the U.S. capital, Sobeih added.
</P>
<P>
"Every time the Israeli side makes a step ahead, it follows up
with ten steps backwards," he said.
</P>
<P>
The current round of talks must reach agreement on such key
issues as halting settlement building, starting redeployment,
addressing both sides' security and deciding on the final status
negotiations, Sobeih further noted.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official called upon the U.S. to apply one
standard in dealing with the Mideast peace process and genuinely
seek to realize peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Arab League (AL) today welcomed the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks in Washington and the U.S. efforts
in this regard, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
AL Assistant Secretary General Ambassador Ahmad Bin Heli
underlined the necessity of making tangible progress in halting
the Israeli settlement building and implementing the articles of
the transitional phase, particularly the redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-backed meeting, the second round of high-level talks
between the Israelis and Palestinians after seven months of
standoff, was postponed from October 27 until today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been at odds over Netanyahu's proposal to
move straight into accelerated "final status" talks that will
tackle more difficult issues like the future of settlements and
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand that Israel first implement
long-delayed withdrawal of Israeli troops in most rural areas of
the West Bank and agree on a freeze in settlement activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
