<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reduction of Zimbabwe's National Debt Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 3 (Xinhua) --The Zimbabwean government has
been urged to make great efforts to reduce national debts,
currently estimated at four billion U.S Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a finance students seminar, dean of
commerce in Zimbabwe's National University of Science and
Technology, Elton Razemba, warned developing nations against
external borrowings, saying this had disadvantages in that
foreign commercial banks lent at very high interest rates which
also included service charges and management fees.
</P>
<P>
''Internal borrowing is not as burdensome as external
borrowing which demands that repayments of the original loan
interest and surcharges have to be paid in foreign currency which
is difficult to procure," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said with internal borrowing, the money would be
circulating among "members of the same family". But, he said,
government borrowings crowded out private sector enterprises,
starving them of funds for investment.
</P>
<P>
Razemba said that it is necesary for the country to keep the
budget deficit around five percent of the Gross Domestic Product
instead of the 10 to 15 percent haunting the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
