<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A regional symposium on promoting
governmental efforts against land mines opened here today with the
participation of 23 Arab countries and a number of international
and non-governmental anti-mines organizations.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium was organized by the Swedish Child
Welfare Organization and the Yemeni Committee on Promotion of
Awareness Against Mines.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed at persuading those countries which have failed to
accede to a special treaty on the prohibition of land mines and
which seek exemptions, to promptly sign the treaty and engage in
international campaign to ban mines, Yemeni news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Yemeni Deputy Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister Abdul Karim Al Iryani said the convocation of
the symposium reflects that Yemen attachs importance of this
issue. He voiced his government's support to international actions
against land mines.
</P>
<P>
He said that land mines pose a threat to human communities in
various parts of the world, particularly Yemen, adding that Yemen
is suffering from such mines which have claimed thousands of
innocent lives and caused heavy economic losses since the
1960s between the former North Yemen and South Yemen. 
</P>
