<HEADLINE> UK Government Reluctant to Interfere in Nanny Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government has
refused to exert diplomatic pressure on the U.S. government on
behalf of the convicted British au pair Louise Woodward, but
saying it followed the developments closely.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Miller, a MP representing Woodward's constituency, early
today discussed with British Foreign Office minister Liz Symons
the case of Woodward, who was found guilty last week in Cambridge,
Massachusetts, of the second degree murder of eight-month-old
Matthew Eappen and was given a mandatory life sentence.
</P>
<P>
The sentence has provoked wide-spread angry reaction across
Britain over the past few days and a fund was established to mount
an appeal campaign.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Symons, Miller said: "The
government obviously cannot and should not seek to interfere in
the judicial system of a well-developed democracy."
</P>
<P>
"But it is important that ministers are aware of what has gone
on so that if the case goes to appeal, pressure is brought through
diplomatic channels to ensure that the appeal is held early."
</P>
<P>
Symons said in a statement issued after the meeting that the
London government was "closely following all developments in the
case". But she gave no indication that any action would be made.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an aide to Prime Minister Tony Blair was reported as
saying: "We are watching it in exactly the same way as everyone
else is."
</P>
<P>
"But it would not be appropriate for the prime minister to take
a view on the verdict," the aide said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
