<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Rejects Challenge to California's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Supreme Court
Monday rejected a challenge to California's Proposition 209, which
bans affirmative action -- a formal effort to provide increased
employment and education opportunities for ethnic minorities and
women -- by any level of state or city government.
</P>
<P>
A coalition of civil rights groups had asked the justices to
hear argument on the challenge this term, but the Supreme Court
denied the request Monday without comment.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers following the case anticipate the rejection might open
the floodgates to similar measures across the country, at least on
the county or municipal level. About 26 jurisdictions are
reportedly poised to enact a similar law.
</P>
<P>
California voters passed Proposition 209 -- the California
Civil Rights Initiative -- in November 1996 by 54 to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Proposition 209 says the state "shall not discriminate against,
or grant preferential treatment to, any individual or group on the
basis of race, sex, color, ethnicity or national origin in the
operation of public employment, public education or public
contracting."
</P>
<P>
Earlier the coalition challenged the law, and a federal judge
in San Francisco issued a preliminary injunction against its
implementation, ruling that the state law conflicted with federal
civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
But a federal appeals court panel threw out the injunction, and
refused to block the effects while the challengers took their case
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court last month refused to suspend Proposition
209, but left open the question of whether it would hear argument
in the case until today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
