<HEADLINE> Iran Echoes German Proposal for Fence-mending Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said today that Tehran welcomes Bonn's proposal of
holding talks to mend relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, Kharrazi made the
remark in Pretoria, South Africa, in a response to a suggestion of
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
IRNA's report did not mention when and how Kinkel raised the
proposal. However, an Iranian source here told Xinhua that
Kharrazi today received a message from his German counterpart.
</P>
<P>
"Kinkel's request will not go unanswered," Kharrazi said, "Iran
welcomes Kinkel's interest in conducting talks that would
facilitate the mending of ties between Iran and Germany for the
normalization of relations."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran would closely scrutinize such proposals,
specifically those from friendly countries, which also assure
Iran's stand on the return of European ambassadors to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The 15 member states of the European Union (EU) withdrew their
ambassadors from Tehran in protest after a Berlin court charged
that Iranian leadership were involved in a political
assassinations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Iran later announced that the EU ambassadors could return to
Tehran but the German envoy must be the last to do so, a formula
seen by Bonn as an attempt to undermine the EU's solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi today still insisted that "the affairs which took
shape in matters of relations between Germany and Iran has hurt
the public feelings of Iranians and that the matter needs to be
somehow and somewhat compensated."
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that if Tehran sticks to its present
position, there will be little room for progress to be made during
its talks with German, its largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi left here Saturday night for an official visit to
South Africa to attend the third Iran-South Africa joint economic
commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
