<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Lawmakers Against Croatian President's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The planned visit to Israel
by Croatian President Franjo Tudjman is creating a political
storm in Israel as some Israeli lawmakers are against the trip for
the alleged anti-Semitic attitude of Tudjman.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry has said that Tudjman planned to
visit Israel next month to realize his promise made in August,
when the two countries established diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman said that he wanted to visit the Jewish state to
apologize personally for crimes committed by some of his people
during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
But some Israeli lawmakers were upset about Tudjman's planned
visit because of what was called his anti-Semitic views.
Lawmakers Yossi Beilin and Yossi Sarid, of the opposition Labor
party and Meretz party, filed on Sunday urgent motions to the
Knesset (Parliament) agenda to protest against Tudjman's visit.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Sarid called Tudjman as an "anti-Semite" who has
denied the Holocaut, adding the president should be considered a
persona non grata in Israel. "If Tudjman does come, he will
encounter stormy protests. Many will be unable to come to terms
with his provocative and painful presence here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said it would be a mistake to allow Tudjman to
visit. "He never took back his serious published statements that
the Holocaust is a Jewish invention and his willingness to
apologize for his people's crimes does not cover up for his
own," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman has long been accused by Israel of making antisemitic
slurs in his writings. Israeli historian Jennie Lebel, who
specializes in Yugoslavian history, charged Tudjman for having
naming public places after leaders of the fascist former Zagreb's
wartime regime which outdid the Nazi SS in massacrering Yugoslavia's
Jews.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that Tudjman, in one of his books, expressed
clearly his antisemitic views. Tudjman was quoted as having said,
"thank God that my wife is neither Serbian nor Jewish."
</P>
<P>
Due to the protests over Tudjman's visit, Israeli President
Ezer Weizman has not decided whether to receive Tudjman, the
Presidential Office said in a statement Sunday night. Visiting
presidents and monarchs are generally guests of the president in
coordination with the Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
