<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Economists Warn of Further Market Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England could
trigger another bout of turmoil in the London stock market if it
raises interest rates this week, leading economists here have
warned.
</P>
<P>
Alan Walters, Lady Thatcher's former economic adviser, and
Professor Patrick Minford from Cardiff Business School urged the
bank's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) to keep base rates
unchanged at 7 percent when it meets Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many City economists expect the bank to raise rates by 0.25
percent, in order to avoid breaching the upper limit of 3.5
percent in the government's inflation target in the future.
</P>
<P>
Some of them even believe that only a new share price collapse
in the next few days might deter the MPC from raising interest
rates 0.25 percent to 7.25 percent this week.
</P>
<P>
"The decision is touch and go at the moment," according to
Barclays economist director Chris Wright.
</P>
<P>
If the committee decides to delay the increase, Wright believes
that it will require a massive fall in share prices to prevent
rates from rising to 7.5 percent before the spring.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead to this week's MPC meeting, Wright said, "The
committee may want to wait (and) see whether October's retail
spending has recovered from September's downturn."
</P>
<P>
"But the bank will be worried about the labor market conditions
which sees average earnings growing at 4.5 percent -- it is the
maximum compatible with achieving the 2.5 percent inflation
tartet," he added.
</P>
<P>
Professor Minford said he did not believe the bank would risk
further market turbulence by raising rates.
</P>
<P>
"After the stock market drop you've got the risk of overkill.
Exchange rates are also high that a rise in interest rates could
trigger further falls in share prices," he argued.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index ended last week 127.9 points lower at
5330.8, having recovered some of its lost ground after a 458 point
plunge at one stage Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the index is still comfortably ahead of the 4057 level
of the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Cates, economist at UBS, noted that although the recent
stock market turbulence will probably not depress domestic demand
much, "an interest rate rise under the current circumstances is
most unlikely." 
</P>
</TEXT>
