<HEADLINE> Mozambique Okays Compulsory Military Service Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Parliament today
passed, with the only favorate vote from the ruling party
parliamentary members, a draft law to resume the the compulsory
Military service system.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory military service law, abandoned in the country
in 1992 in accordance with the peace agreement, got green light with
124 for, 103 against and eight abstentions at the parliament
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Men aging from 18 to 35 are obligated to serve in the army
according to the draft law.
</P>
<P>
The law, favored by the ruling Liberation Front of Mozambique
(Frelimo) which took the majority in number at the
parliament, met objection from the National Resistance of
Mozambique (Renamo), the major opposition party in the country and
the Democratic Union, the third biggest party in the country.
</P>
<P>
All the Renamo members left the meeting after they voted
against such move forwarded by the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Union members abstained from voting for the
law.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Viera, representative of the ruling Frelimo said after
the law was passed, that it is the responsibility of every
Mozambican to safeguard his country.
</P>
<P>
But the Renamo said in a communique against the law that the fate
of Mozambican men below the age of 35 would have to be at the
hands of the ruling party, with university students suffering
the most.
</P>
<P>
Raul Domingos, Renamo leader said at the opening of the
parliamentary meeting that there should have been a national
referendum for such a move which has impact on the whole
nation.
</P>
<P>
According to the peace agreement, the country could have a
30,000-strong army, but there are only 11,000 army men in the
country as the government finds it difficult to recruit
soldiers. Endite



=11032030

=11032032
NNNN
04:29 04:29 g # PAB
</P>
