<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tietmeyer Rules Out Early Coordination of European Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Bundesbank President Hans
Tietmeyer today ruled out early coordination of European interest
rates in the run-up to the 1999 start-up of the single European
currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
The level of European interest rates depended on both economic
data and the states selected to join the euro, said the head of
German central bank while addressing a meeting of tax advisers in
the German city of Aashen.
</P>
<P>
European leaders are scheduled to meet in May next year to
decide which countries qualify for membership of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer insisted in his speech that Bundesbank's decision
last month to raise its key money market rate, the repo, from 3 to
3.3 percent, was made to guard against inflation prior to the
launch of the euro.
</P>
<P>
Analysts had viewed the rise as representing the first step
towards concerting European interest rates ahead of the euro.
Considering the huge gaps between rates in various countries, they
had expected the Bundesbank to continue edging up its rates next
year in preparation for bigger move to harmonize European rates.
</P>
<P>
They had believed that the repo rate would rise again by the
end of this year and would reach 4 percent by around the middle of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Holger Fahringkrug, economist with the Union Bank of
Switzerland in Frankfurt, noted that Tietmeyer's remarks did not
necessarily exclude a rate rise based on domestic factors, such as
inflation and the M3 money supply.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
