<HEADLINE> S. Africa Urges Cooperation to Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today urged
Southern African countries to join hands in the fight against poverty,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
There was an urgent need for Southern African states to work
together to fight poverty, Deputy Minister in the Deputy President's
Office, Essop Pahad, told a U.N. forum.
</P>
<P>
The fight against poverty in Southern Africa would only be won
through the cooperation of governments and other stakeholders, Pahad
said at the U.N. Forum on Poverty Eradication in Midrand, a town lies
midway between Johannesburg and Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa is committed to all UN programs aimed at
addressing the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We acknowledge all U.N. programs on poverty, including a declaration
on poverty to run from 1997 to 2007," Pahad said.
</P>
<P>
South African-based U.N. Information Center director Yobert
Shamapande said he believed democracy and democratic institutions
would not take root or endure in an environment where the vast
majority of people were overwhelmed by abject poverty without access
to basic human needs.
</P>
<P>
"Democracy and democratic institutions will certainly be under
threat in an environment of continuous conflicts, social exclusions
and neglect which has characterized the region over the past decade,"
Shamapande said.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the three-day forum are to follow up and promote
concrete action on recitations and decisions made at UN international
conferences, especially the World Social Summit held in Copenhagen,
Denmark, aimed at eradicating poverty, creating employment
opportunities and enhancing social integration.
</P>
<P>
There was general agreement that real peace in Southern Africa
would only be achieved by tackling the remaining threats stemming from
widespread conditions of poverty, hunger, lack of housing, basic
education and primary health care, all of which precipitated social
disintegration.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the wealthiest country in the region, about 45.7
percent of the population lived in poverty, 98 percent of whom are
blacks, according to a survey conducted in mid-October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
