<HEADLINE> Turkish Army Chief: Maneuvers Not to Turn to War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish military leader denied
here this evening that the two military maneuvers staged by the
Turkish Armed Forces in and near northern Cyprus would turn to war
with Greeks and Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karaday
said, "It is unnecessary to talk about war. It's impossible that
the maneuvers will turn to war."
</P>
<P>
Turkey started a military exercise, code-named Determination
'97, on Saturday and started another one, code-named Toros 2/97,
today in the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish war games were apparently in response to the
three-day joint Greek and Greek Cypriots' military exercises in
the Greek Cypriot-controlled area on October 10-13.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Greece have been worsening
since the Cypriot government announced that it would not give up
the controversial plan to buy 150-kilometer-range anti-aircraft
S-300 missiles from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said today in Istanbul
that the existing problems between Turkey and Greece are "so
sensitive that both countries should deal with them calmly."
</P>
<P>
He said: "In Madrid, we signed a declaration together with
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis. In that declaration, it was
said that 'let's solve the problems between the two countries by
peaceful ways'. Of course, these problems are so
sensitive. However, the peaceful way to solution is still open."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Defense Minister
Ismet Sezgin left Turkey today for northern Cyprus to watch the
two continuing maneuvers in and near Cyprus, showing that Turkey
has attached great importance to the military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin said Sunday that the Turkish government was staging
military exercises in and near Cyprus, not a war, adding: "there
will be a clash in the Aegean if Greece wants it."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli told
reporters "We hope there will not be any hot clashes" during
the military exercises staged by Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), have experienced increased tension because
of their frequent exercises in the Aegean and the Cyprus'
missile plan.
</P>
<P>
The tension between the two NATO members has caused grave
concern among Balkan countries, which urge the two neighbors to
exercise restraint.
</P>
<P>
Ankara and Athens have long been at odds over a number of
issues, including airspace division, mineral resources under the
Aegean and the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
