<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Launch Case Against Accused Oklahoma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. federal prosecutors
today started producing evidence in the murder and conspiracy
trial of Terry Nichols in Denver, Colorado, saying he was
responsible for the Oklahoma City bombing even though he was far
away from the scene when it happened.
</P>
<P>
Nichols, the accused accomplice of convicted bomber Timothy
McVeigh, was home in Herington, Kansas, when the truck bomb
exploded on April 19, 1995, but he helped buy and hide the bomb's
ingredients, stole money to fund the plot and stashed McVeigh's
getaway car, prosecutor Larry Mackey said in his opening
statement.
</P>
<P>
The explosion killed 168 people, including 19 children, and
injured more than 500 others.
</P>
<P>
"During the months before that day, Terry Nichols had been side
by side with Tim McVeigh, together in their plan of violence,"
reports quoted Mackey as telling the jury.
</P>
<P>
Nichols, 42, faces the same 11 conspiracy and murder charges as
his Army buddy McVeigh, who was convicted on June 2 and sentenced
to death 11 days later.
</P>
<P>
Defense attorney Michael Tigar, whose opening statement began
after that of the prosecutor, was expected to argue that Nichols
was not part of McVeigh's bombing plan and to stress Nichols'
alibi on the morning of the blast.
</P>
<P>
But the prosecutor revealed that Nichols' image was captured
months before by a security camera in a coin shop in Wichita,
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
The photographs link Nichols to phone calls made immediately
afterward from a phone booth across the street to vendors of
barrels like those used in the massive truck bomb, Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
Mackey also said the government has significant physical
evidence connecting Nichols to the bombing, including blasting
cord and caps, a drill bit used in a robbery to steal supplies and
guns stolen to raise money for the scheme.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh was arrested on the day of the bombing, driving away
from Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
Nichols turned himself in to police two days later after
hearing his name on the radio in connection with the bombing.
McVeigh had used the address of Nichols' brother James on a motel
registration card, prompting an FBI raid on the family's remote
farm in Decker, Michigan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
