<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project a Ecology-Prone Project: Expert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 4 (Xinhua) -- "The Three
Gorges Project is an ecological project," said Lu Youmei,
president of the China Three Gorges Project Development Corp. during
his meeting with a senior French official.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who once served as vice-minister of water conservancy and
power and vice-minister of energy, held that China should speed up
efforts on ecological and environmental improvement along the
Yangtze, in which the Three Gorges Project could play its part.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also indicated that the Chinese government has
attached great importance to ecological problems that may possibly
crop up during the construction of the project.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze valley, particularly at its middle and lower
reaches, cited as the cream of the Chinese economy, is also a
region that has frequented by floods and other natural disasters.
In this century alone, three catastrophic floods occurred in the
1930s and 1950s took a toll of more than 300,000 lives and caused
tremeous economic losses.
</P>
<P>
The anti-flood effort of the project has so far provided an
ecological shield for this economically developed region, the
Jingjiang River valley in partucular, Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
This region, with a population of 15 million with 1.53 million
hectares of farmland, now can cope with a catastrophic flood of a
ten-year frequency.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the project, Jingjiang river region will be
able to combat flood that may occur once every 100 years.
</P>
<P>
Energy shortage is a big hindrance to the sustained growth of
the Chinese economy on the long run. China's energy consumption
after 1990 registered an annual growth of 4 percent and there is
an accelerated trend," Lu added. The coal-burning-dominant energy
structure, however, could worsen such eco-problems.
</P>
<P>
This world's largest hydro-power station is designed to ease the
energy shortage and improve the eco-environment.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimated that in comparison with thermal power plants
of the same generation capacity, the Three Gorges Project, with an
installed generation capacity of 18.2 megawatts, can save 50
million tons of raw coal and cut 100 million tons of carbon
dioxide, and reduce large amounts of dust, sewage and
discarded residue.
</P>
<P>
People are also concerned with fact that the slower waterflow
in the future reservoir may weaken the Yangtze's self-cleaning
capability in discharging and washing off the toxic contents
poured by shoreside industries.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with a famous Chinese writer, Gan Yuping,
vice-mayor of Chongqing Municipality, said that the Three Gorges
project will not be turned into a cesspool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project a Ecology-Prone Project: Expert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gan listed several figures to elaborate his point. Annual
runoff stands around 451 billion c.m. in the area of the future
reservoir area, whose storage capacity is projected to reach 39.3
billion c.m. "The water in the reservoir can be changed about ten
times a year," he said. Currently, some one billion tons of
liquid sewage is discharged into the Yangtze, one one four hundredth
of the annual runoff.
</P>
<P>
As part of the effort to speed up sewage treatment, more than
20 water disposal plants will be built on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze, and Chongqing alone will build five such factories, Gan
noted.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, a number of small enterprises, including small
paper mills, will be closed. Upon hearing the news, Tan Dexun, a
farmer who has been living in a village by the Yangtze for more
than 70 years, said: "This will surely help improve our living
environment."
</P>
<P>
A Chinese environmental official said, "We promise that no
industrial waste and sewage will be released into the Yangtze
without undergoing treatment upon completion of the project."
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the China State Environment Protection
Agency, said the Chinese government has founded an
ecological-protection organ pertaining to the Three Gorges
Project, with 13 eco-supervisory networks on relocation of people,
hydrology, hydrography and other fields, and conducted a an
all-round ecological survey mainly at the dam site and the source
of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese government also launched a
diversified biological protection program in the Three Gorges
area.
</P>
<P>
The state has planned to set up three animal reserves and 12
fish-egg hatching grounds, and rare fish species in the upper
reaches, rare aquatics in the middle reaches and Chinese
alligators in the lower reach will be protected properly.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges region is also a place where rare plant
species grown in profusion. Botanists have designated Dalaoling
Mountain in Yichang, Jiugong Mountain and Wuhan Botanical Garden
as the new "homes" of the rare plants.
</P>
<P>
According to a researcher with Wuhan Botanical Institute under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, some 80 percent of the
transplanted species have acclimatized to the new environment. And
certain species will return to the reservoir area after the
completion of the project. "All species survived from the glacier
of the Quaternary Period will not disappear for the construction
of the Three Gorges," the research said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
