<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Territorial Resolution Comes First: Hashimoto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said today that the resolution of the country's
territorial row with Russia should precede the conclusion of a
peace treaty between the two countries, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
That's why the two countries mentioned in their latest
agreement, the 1993 Tokyo Declaration, the early conclusion of a
peace treaty through resolving the territorial dispute, Hashimoto
told reporters in the Diet (parliament) building.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese prime minister made the remark while referring to
Russian reports that a peace treaty and the territorial dispute
were separate issues.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto and Russian President Boris Yeltsin agreed in their
first informal summit last weekend in Krasnoyarsk, eastern
Siberia, to make their utmost efforts to sign a peace treaty by
2000 on the basis of the 1993 Tokyo Declaration.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Japan and Russia agreed to work to
normalize their diplomatic relations by resolving the dispute on
the basis of "the principles of law and justice."
</P>
<P>
The territorial dispute over the Russian-held islands --
Etorofu, Kunashiri, Shikotan and the Habomai group of islets --
has prevented the two countries from signing a peace treaty for
more than five decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
