<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Stresses Progress in Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Both sides of the Sino-Portuguese
Joint Liaison Group (JLG) stressed here today that new progress
should be made in resolving the major issues during Macao's
transitional period.
</P>
<P>
Both Han Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side of
the Sino-Portuguese JLG, and his Portuguese counterpart, Antonio
Santana Carlos, stressed the importance of the localization of
civil service, the localization of law and the use of Chinese as
an official language when they finished the first-day meeting of
the 30th plenary session of the JLG.
</P>
<P>
at today's meeting, the Portuguese side briefed the Chinese
side on the progress made on those three major issues. The Chinese
side, in return, urged the Portuguese side to take further
concrete measures to step up the process.
</P>
<P>
"The related work should be stepped up and concrete measures
should be taken in the localization of civil service, especially,
the middle and senior ranking posts," Han said. "There should come
a major progress and a breakthrough as there is only a little more
than two years left before the handover in 1999."
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Chinese ambassador said that the use of
Chinese as an official language should be implemented at a full
scale within the period of transition.
</P>
<P>
Carlos said that the Portuguese side is very concerned with the
localization of the civil service as it is of vital importance for
a smooth transition. He said the Macao Government has made great
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Carlos also expressed his hope that the speed in reviewing laws
would be quickened as there are still a great amount of laws
remaining to be examined and localized.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will continue tomorrow, and a joint press release
is expected to be issued when the session concludes later
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
