<HEADLINE> Iraq Asks for Stopping US Spy Plane Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq again asked the United
Nations Special Committee (UNSCOM) on dismantling Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction to prevent an U.S. say plane from hovering in
its airspace.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraqi News Agency, the Iraqi government said
the U-2 surveillance plane was spying on Iraq for the U.S. and was
not working for the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
This request came in a message handed over by Nazar Hamdoun,
Iraq's permanent representative to the U.N., to Richard Butler,
head of the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The message voiced Iraq's willingness to hammer out, in
collaboration with the UNSCOM, a U.N. Security Council-approved
formula for the committee using such type of planes in Iraqi
airspace.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had last month suggested substituting the U.S. plane
operating in Iraqi airspace with an Iraqi plane to be put at the
disposal of the UNSCOM, or using an alternative plane from a
neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The message made it clear that, in the light of the present
developments, the U.S. is expected to launch a military attack
against Iraq, so it is unacceptable for an American spy plane to
get into Iraqi airspace.
</P>
<P>
The message held Butler responsible for the consequences if he
decides to authorize the U.S. plane to go ahead with its mission.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials today refused to allow U.S. personnel to take
part in a U.N. inspection of a suspected missile storage site in
Baghdad for a second day. The U.N. team then canceled the
inspection.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has ordered all U.S. weapon inspectors working with the
UNSCOM to leave Iraq by Wednesday, accusing them of espionage.
</P>
</TEXT>
