<HEADLINE> GCC Petrochemical Conference Opens in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The fifth Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) petrochemicals and fertilizers conference opened
here today aimed at promoting cooperation among the GCC states in
this sector.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference jointly sponsored by the GCC
Secretariat, the Kuwait Petrochemical Industries Company and a
number of GCC petrochemical companies attracted dozens of
participants.
</P>
<P>
The conference aims at coordinating production, investment and
technological research in the field of petrochemicals, Kuwaiti
Minister of Oil Issa Al-Mazidi said at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A series of seminars, lectures and exhibitions would be held
on the sidelines of the conference, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to GCC assistant secretary general for economic
affairs Abdallah Al-Khleifi, the GCC states, namely Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain, have
formed a committee to coordinate cooperation in the field of
petroleum and petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states were keen on promoting economic and commercial
coordination with the major companies to integrate with the
international economic systems in a bid to have access to the
international markets, the GCC official said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed companies and businessmen to invest in this
encouraging and vital economic sector.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states have 45 percent of the world's proven oil
reserves. Recent years witnessed a large demand for expansion in
the field of the petrochemical industry in the GCC states as the
consumption of petrochemical products has been on the increase
in the international markets as well as within the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
GCC petrochemical exports in 1996 valued at around 3.8
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
