<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Forces FIFA to Keep Original Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Football
Federation has agreed to restore Japan's vital World Cup qualifier
against Kazakhstan to its original date - Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA sent fax message to all the countries involved on
Monday, suggesting Japan to play Kazakhstan and the United Arab
Emirates to play South Korea at the same time on Sunday. That
means that Japan has to change the game schedule from Saturday to
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA's move was to make sure that neither side had the
advantage of knowing the result of the other.
</P>
<P>
But Japan complained that the stadium would be used for an
athletics meeting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Football Association (JFA) general secretary Junji
Ogura had planned to fly to Zurich in a bid to let FIFA stick to
the original time.
</P>
<P>
FIFA bowed to the pressure and Japan now will go ahead with its
match on Saturday -- 24 hours before the Emirates play South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the Emirates are in contention for second place in
the group, which would put them in a play-off for a World Cup
place. South Korea have already qualified for next year's finals.
</P>
<P>
Japan moved to second in the group by beating South Korea 2-0
last weekend when the UAE were held 0-0 by Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and Japan will co-host the 2002 World Cup finals
and Japan is desperate to avoid becoming the only nation to host
the event without ever having played in a World Cup final.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Results of Men's World Open Squash Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are the first
