<HEADLINE> Pak Chief Justice Calls for Efforts to Normalize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief Justice of Pakistan's
Supreme Court Sajjad Ali Shah said here today that collective
efforts should be made to normalize the present situation.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether there is any threat to democracy, the apex court
chief justice said that "all should help to normalize the
matters", adding the media should also give a helping hand.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad made his remarks to the local media after administering
oath to the newly elevated five judges of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad said he had made recommendations to elevate the judges
in accordance with the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"The basic objective before us is the smooth functioning of the
institutions, according to the constitution," he added.
</P>
<P>
The five judges of the Supreme Court recommended by the chief
justice today took oath of office formally, putting an end to the
constitutional grid lock that had hit the country for more than
two months.
</P>
<P>
The number of judges in the apex court now has been fixed at 17
after the elevation today of the five new judges. Sajjad said he
will make a decision for a full court meeting later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
