<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Disciplinary Official Sets Anti-Corruption Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 4 (Xinhua) -- China's anti-corruption
campaign will focus on banning gifts at meetings and conferences,
and the use of public funds to install home telephones or to buy
mobile phones, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, secretary of the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection, said during a recent tour of east China's
Zhejiang Province that the ban should be the central task for
disciplinary departments at all levels in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we should settle a group of serious corruption
cases in the shortest possible time as part of our effort to carry
out the guidelines of the 15th National Party Congress," said Wei
who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
He called for building up a "legal front-line for fighting
corruption within the Party," so that "there will be no hiding
places for graft."
</P>
<P>
Education should be stressed at the same time as prevention.
"We need a moral front-line as well," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei urged enhanced supervision, especially to check on leading
officials. At the grass-roots level, he said, a democratic
supervision process should be put in place, which should promote
an open system of administration and budget management.
</P>
<P>
Deepening the political restructuring, institutions and
administration should also be put on the agenda to rid the soil
that helps breed corruption, Wei said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
