<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time Not Ripe for Afghan Peace, says Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan can hardly make
substantial progress in its peace-finding process unless the
conditions are ripe, a United Nations special envoy said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Internal and the external factors were not ready for peace in
the country," Norbert Holl said in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua, at the U.N. Special Mission for Afghanistan (UNSMA), here.
</P>
<P>
Holl said there is not "sufficient sense of compromise among
all Afghan parties." Secondly, parties with influence "had yet to
seriously discuss with the U.N. mission how to get out of the
Afghanistan dilemma," he said.
</P>
<P>
The German diplomat, who was appointed the UNSMA head in July
last year and resigned recently, said: "I have a little difficulty
to accept that the U.N. has failed."
</P>
<P>
Holl said: "The only thing the U.N. is trying here is to give a
helping hand to the Afghans in finding peace."
</P>
<P>
"It is up to the Afghans and only to the Afghans to find a way
to peace. If someone has failed to find peace, it is first of all
the Afghans."
</P>
<P>
"It is not failure. It is the lack of appropriate political
instruments which caused the developments of the past five years,"
Holl added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
