<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rules for Internet Must Suit Social Background, Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua)-- Each country should establish
laws, rules and ethics in accordance with its own social
background to govern the use of the Internet, so that the
information industry will make greater and healthier contributions
to the mankind in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Lin Quan, secretary-general of the State Science and Technology
Commission, made the remarks today at a seminar titled
"Inforamtion Imperative: Rules of the Road for the Internet",
attended by both Chinese and U.S. information officials and
experts.
</P>
<P>
Lin said, the Internet, as the craddle of the information age,
has exerted prefound impact on the work mode and living style of
the mankind. "In discussing the rules governing the use of the
Internet, it is important to remind that the rules must be made in
accordance with the United Nations acknowledged principles, in
respect of the different political systems and economic
development and cultural background of various countries. We
should avoid enlarging the gap between developed and developing
countries in the course of information globalization and we should
arouse our concern over the dissemination of harmful information
while expanding the Internet," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial statistics, China now has 500,000
Internet subscribers, most of whom are businesses, government
organs and scientific and cultural institutions in the more
developed eastern part of the country. China also has a growing
number of family-based subscribers, but the percentage is
relatively small.
</P>
<P>
Lin said Chinese parents have realized that the Internet
contains information of low taste that is not suited to their
children and have taken steps to educate them not to read those
information. But, he said, the measures focus on ethical education
instead of exerting fast rules. "The country has not yet set up
any rules and regulations to control the access to the Internet,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization convened last March on the ethics and rules
over the Internet and did not result in a universal rule as the
delegates varied in their opinions on a lot of issues. But he
said the conference was useful for Chinese and foreign experts to
further discuss the issues in order to exchange ideas and increase
understanding.
</P>
<P>
Lin Quan told the seminar that the Iinternet, that originated
in the United States, was first introduced to China in 1993 and
has flourished over the past four years. And it will develop rapidly
with the fast growth of the country's telecommunications
and computer industries.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin, China has established four major national
inforamtion networks that have access to the Internet. They
are ChinaNet run by the Ministry of Post and Telecommunications,
CERNET by the State Education Commission, NCFC by the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and STINET by the State Science and Technology
Commission. In addition, information service companies that are
hooked up to the Internet platform have also mushroomed all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was co-organized by the State Science and
Technology Commission, the United Nations Development Program and
the World Times Inc. of the United States. It was sponsored by
American AT&AMP;T, International Data Group Asia and Digital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0103 </DOCNO>
