<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Software Developer Signs Pact With IBM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang Alpine Software Ltd.,
one of China's biggest software developers, will be backed by IBM
in developing new products and marketing programs.
</P>
<P>
The two companies signed a business partnership agreement today
in Shenyang, capital of northeastern China's Liaoning
Province. The ceremony was attended by Liu Jiren, general manager
of the software company, and Stanley Krasnow, a senior manager of
IBM.
</P>
<P>
The companies will jointly develop software, provide consulting
services, and launch a marketing program for automatic office
equipment and other new products in six Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang Alpine Software Ltd. is a Sino-Japanese joint venture
formed in 1991 between Northeast China University and Alpine
Co. Ltd. of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Shenyang company has set up the first national software
development center, China's largest, and is selling more than 40
different products to thousands of domestic and overseas
businesses.  
