<HEADLINE> China's Population Not More Than 1.4 Billion By 2010: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- China expects to limit its
population to less than 1.4 billion by the year 2010, according to
the country's top family planning official.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, China, the most populous country in the
world, should first control the population to less than 1.3
billion and largely reduce the incidence of congenital birth
defects, said Zhang Weiqing, vice-minister of the State Family
Planning Commission (SFPC).
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the remark at a national SFPC meeting held today in
Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the country's population will steadily
decrease after China scores zero population growth around 2050,
and population quality in terms of health and education will be
remarkably improved.  
</P>
