<HEADLINE> Hamburg SPD, Greens to Form State Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The Social Democrats (SPD) and the
leftist-environmentalist Green alliance (GAL) in the northern
German port city of Hamburg have agreed to form a coalition
government to rule the city-state in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
After 13 rounds of talks, they agreed Monday that the Green
alliance will hold three cabinet posts and control the ministries
concerning environment, urban planning, science and higher
education and European policy.
</P>
<P>
The SPD will control the ministries for economy, schools,
welfare, culture, justice, internal affairs and construction.
</P>
<P>
The SPD mayor designate Ortwin Runde noted that "no conflicts
were swept under the carpet" during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Social Democrats lost their previous independent Statt Partei
coalition partner in the September 21 regional elections. The SPD
saw the worst post-war election result in its northern stronghold,
gaining 36.2 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
The conservative Christian Democratic Union of German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl won 30.7 percent of the vote and the GAL
13.9 percent. No other party met the five percent mark necessary
for any seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Hamburg elections are regarded as an indicator for
Germany's 1998 general elections. Analysts took a close interest
to see what kind of coalition government was formed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
