<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Economic Woes Force PM to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh Monday finally decided to resign, a move which is a
surprise to some people, but may not be so surprising to many
others as the country's economy continues to be in a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit announced his resignation at a time when the country's
currency, the baht, suffered a fresh bout of plunging recently,
hitting a record low of more than 41 baht against the U.S. dollar
last weekend. It seems that the unchecked fall of the baht is the
most direct reason for Chavalit to choose to leave.
</P>
<P>
The stability of the baht has been the focus of concern over
the country's economic situation this year and the Thai government
spent a huge amount of its foreign reserves in mid-May to defend
the currency against speculation.
</P>
<P>
However, with the country's foreign exchange reserves depleting
significantly, the government found it difficult to maintain the
stability of the baht with the limited foreign reserves.
Therefore, it took the radical step of floating the baht on July
2, leading to a further reduction in the country's foreign
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Besides, in exchange for aid from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to overcome the economic difficulty, the government had
to implement radical economic reform measures, which it had hoped
would help restore the confidence of investors and bring the
economy back on the track in the long run. Instead, the measures
led to a free-fall of the baht, rising inflation and increasing
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the financial sector failed to see an immediate
improvement in liquidity and the problems of the 58 cash-tight
finance firms, whose operations were suspended by the government
according to the IMF requirements, remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
As the measures introduced by the government were affecting
more and more people, the public's resentment against the Chavalit
government was mounting and the call for the change of government
rising.
</P>
<P>
The Chavalit cabinet has long been believed to lack a strong
economic team to run the country's economy. Chavalit had been
following the policy of inviting non-party economic experts to
assume the key economic posts in the cabinet, but the policy
appeared to be unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
Former Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay
Virawan offered in late June this year to resign, saying he failed
to make the country's economy turn for the better. In October,
former Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya, who succeeded Amnuay, also
chose to quit due to the country's economic woes. The frequent
changes of key cabinet members adversely affected the confidence
of investors.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made the last cabinet reshuffle on October 24 under
pressure from both the public and the coalition partners in the
hope that the six-party coalition government would survive until
the next general election scheduled for early next year. But the
reshuffle neither boosted the public's morale nor stopped the baht
from declining further.
</P>
<P>
And the continuous fall of the baht also frustrated the
public's confidence in the country's overall economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit came to power at a time when the country was already
seeing an economic slowdown and he had tried every possible way,
including some bold steps, to restructure the country's economy.
However, his effort proved futile although the prime minister said
he had done his best.
</P>
<P>
In deciding to resign, Chavalit has shown a great spirit of
self-sacrifice and he has done so in the hope of reviving public
confidence in the country's economy and thus benefiting the
country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Yet, whoever will replace him will find that there is no easy
way to redress the country's economic woes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
