<HEADLINE> Changes in Members of Chinese Industrial And Commercial Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The membership structure of the
All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce (ACFIC) has been
changed a lot in recent years, with the non-public economic sector
being better represented.
</P>
<P>
The non-public sector has gone from 205,900 members in 1993 to
the present 684,800, which is 58 percent of total membership,
according to ACFIC's Eighth Congress, which opened Monday in
Beijing,
</P>
<P>
ACFIC now has 1,166,80 members, a 74.15 percent increase from
1993, and 52 percent of the executive committee members are from
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
ACIFC was founded in 1953, and it was organized by industrial
and commercial groups as a sort of chamber of commerce and is
under the leadership of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
It comprises non-public firms, share-holding enterprises,
state-owned firms, and private business people.  
</P>
