<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's tourism suffered a 6 percent decrease in
August in the number of visitors compared to the same period last
year, the Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Tourism Ministry as saying that 202,300
foreign visitors entered the country in August compared to 215,200
tourists in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The unstable security situation, linked to the stalled Middle
East peace process, had been attributed to the setback of the
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Hotel Association economic adviser Pnina Ben-David said
the situation was worse than the ministry's statistics reveal.
</P>
<P>
Based on hotel stays by foreign tourists, Ben-David said that
in the first eight months of the year, tourism dropped by 8 to 9
percent compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia had achieved continued economic
growth in the first nine months of this year and indications show
that the kingdom will maintain the trend, the Kuwaiti News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia realized an 8.6 percent growth in 1996 gross
domestic product and preliminary estimates suggested a similar
growth rate this year, Hamad Al-Siari, governor of the Saudi
Monetary Agency in charge of the monetary policy, said in his
annual address to Saudi King Fahd and government officials Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said Saudi oil revenues, which were still the main source of
state income, would be marginally higher this year than last
year's 11 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the budget deficit, he said it reduced from 14.6
percent (of the GDP) in 1992 to 3.7 percent last year. He hoped
that the trend would continue to help balance the budget by 2000,
the end the current five year development plan.
</P>
<P>
Saudi industrial sector was also expected to attain growth, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the performance of Saudi banks, the governor said they were
playing an exemplary role in serving the national economy, adding
that the volume of deposits increased in the first eight months of
this year by an average of 2.6 percent to about 221 billion riyals
(58.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that Saudi stock market witnessed in the first nine
months of this year 186 percent increase in the value of traded
shares compared to the corresponding period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the private sector which was playing an increasing role in
the Saudi economy, Al-Siari said the sector had invested more and
more funds in various government projects.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's national carrier Royal Jordanian (RJ) had
joined hands with the Trans World Airline (TWA) to reach more
cities in the United States through TWA's extensive U.S.
network, the Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the "Code Sharing Agreement" with TWA, RJ had expanded
its operations to new U.S. destinations as Detroit, "which was an
immediate success," said RJ President Nader Dahabi at a press
conference following the opening session of the International Air
Transport Association's (IATA) 53rd general assembly held here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between RJ and TWA was made possible after
almost two years of negotiations and planning and was now an
integral part of the ongoing restructuring program of RJ, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Royal Jordanian carried about 1.3 million passengers in 1996
and more than 1.1 million in the first 10 months of this year,
according to Dahabi.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The International Air Transport Association (IATA)
was not proposing an increase in air fare, the Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after opening the 53rd IATA general
assembly here Monday, IATA President Pierre Jeanniot said world
airlines were waging a fare war, and that rise of fuel cost would
affect airlines' profits in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Most airlines wanted to increase air fare due to rise of fuel
cost, but fierce competition had made them hesitate to do so,
Jeanniot said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the profit of world air transport this year
would reach 4.5 billion U.S. dollars, 1.5 billion more than that
of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
