<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania, Yugoslavia to Thaw Old Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Fatos
Nano and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic met Monday for the
first summit between the two countries in half a century and the
two agreed to set about normalizing long-frozen bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Meeting on the sideline of a summit of Balkan leaders in Crete,
Greece, the two leaders discussed the current situation in their
countries and agreed to increase contacts, the Albanian press
reported.
</P>
<P>
Nano said the 90-minute meeting, the first Albanian-Yugoslav
summit since 1947, "created conditions for thawing ties and
opening up dialogue between the two Balkan neighbors."
</P>
<P>
He said he had proposed the two sides increase
contacts. Albania was ready to sign accords with Yugoslavia to
boost bilateral cooperation, especially to promote personnel
contacts, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Personnel contacts require plenty of prior political
contacts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic described the talks as "fruitful" and a "first step"
leading to closer relations.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to start the process of normalization of
relations between Yugoslavia and Albania. I consider it to be a
very important step for a beginning," Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
"After 50 years of frozen relations between Yugoslavia and
Albania, we had the first opportunity for talks. I think the talks
were interesting and, I hope, beneficial to both of us," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed the position of the Albanian
population in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. Nano asked Milosevic
to talk with Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
While admitting that the Kosovo problem exists, Milosevic
insisted the issue was "an internal issue of Yugoslavia, an issue
about a Yugoslav ethnic minority." 
</P>
</TEXT>
