<HEADLINE> Reports Confirm Ethiopian Ammunition Consignment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Reports from the southern
Somali town of Kismaio have confirmed the arrival of ammunition
consignment from Ethiopia five days ago.
</P>
<P>
The ammunition, which consisted of five tons of miscellaneous
small arms rounds, RPGs, heavy machine guns, anti-personnel mines
and attack grenades, was brought on a Hercules plane belonging to
the Ethiopian national air force.
</P>
<P>
According to a reliable eyewitness in Kismaio, the plane
carrying the ammunition and two Somali warlords, General Mohamed
Said Hirsi Morgan and the Ogaden Colonel, Ahmed Hashi Mohamud,
flew from the border town of Dolow controlled by the Ethiopian
forces.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitness also said that the ammunition is now being
stored in the command control center of General Morgan in
Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the weapons in Kismaio, 500 km south of the
capital Mogadishu, pleased the morale of Morgan's militiamen who
have borne a long standing animosity with Hussein Mohamed Aidid's
Habar Gidir clan and a good portion of the Marehan clan.
</P>
<P>
Morgan fully supports the Ethiopian-backed National Salvation
Council (NSC) formed in Sodare village of Ethiopia early this
year.
</P>
<P>
This new ammunition consignment may undermine the current
Egyptian efforts in convening a reconciliation meeting among the
warring parties of the NSC and Hussein Aidid. Leaders of both
sides are now in the Egyptian capital of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
There's no word yet from the factions opposing the NSC over
the arrival of the ammunition.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that the current Ethiopian government
sends ammunition to Somalia defying the U.N. resolution 733 which
imposed weapons embargo on Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 tons of ammunition is confirmed to have been sent
to Somalia by the Ethiopian government since January this year.
</P>
<P>
Morgan was visiting Ethiopia since last month at the
invitation of the Ethiopian army officials.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Morgan, General Omar Hagi Masalle (chairman of
the Marehan clan), and Colonel Mohamud met the Ethiopian defense
minister and discussed about a possible elimination of the Muslim
fundamentalist group of Al-Itihad based in the Lower and Middle
Jubba regions of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia still remains in control of the three main Somali
border towns of Dolow, Bulo Hawo and Luq following its alleged
trace for Muslim fundamentalists in June this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
