<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economic, Trade Mission Going To South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- An 80-member Chinese economic
and trade delegation, headed by Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng, left here today for an
11-day visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is made up of Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, State Planning Commission, and Ministry of the
Metallurgical Industry officials, and executives of 50 large
companies. It was invited by South Africa's Minister of Trade and
Industry Alec Erwin and is the largest Chinese delegation ever to
go to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Shi said he hopes the two countries' government departments and
enterprises will exchange views during the visit to help expand
bilateral long-term economic and trade co-operation.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is China's largest African trading
partner. Bilateral trade volume in 1996 was 1.35 billion US
dollars, compared with 14.65 million US dollars in
1991. China-South Africa trade was 1.1 billion US dollars in the
first nine months of this year, up 15 percent from the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese firms have 40 offices or branches in South Africa, and
100 million US dollars in investment in industry, agriculture,
trade, service, and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Shi said the purpose of the visit is to "demonstrate to the
South African government and business people the confidence and
determination of the Chinese government in developing economic and
trade co-operation with that country."
</P>
<P>
He said China and South Africa can supplement each other. China
can import mineral products, and mining equipment and technology
it needs, and provide machinery and electrical products, light
industrial products, textiles, and chemicals to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
China and South Africa are expected to sign a series of trade
agreements and investment accords. Members of the delegation will
also participate in local trade seminars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
