<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standard Chartered, Sun Hung Kai Ink Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered, one of
the oldest banks in Hong Kong, entered into an agreement today
with the leading property developer, Sun Hung Kai, on the purchase
of new office space in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The bank is paying 1.3 billion HK dollars (167 million U.S.
dollars) for 15 floors in Tower Two of a twin tower project,
Millennium City, developed by Sun Hung Kai Properties in Kwun
Tong, a traditional industrial area in eastern Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these floors, the bank has the option to lease
or buy the next five floors of the tower, which is to be named
after Standard Chartered.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference here today, David Brougham, group
executive director of the bank, said, "Standard Chartered is
investing heavily in Hong Kong and the agreement is a clear,
billion dollar commitment to the growth and development of our
business."
</P>
<P>
"It is an expression of our faith in the future of this great
city and its continuing prosperity," he noted.
</P>
<P>
After it is ready for occupation in the fourth quarter of 1998,
the tower will bring under one roof around 2,000 staff of the bank
currently scattered in different premises around Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Millennium City is the largest commercial development in Kwun
Tong and is leading Kwun Tong's transformation from an industrial
area into a thriving commercial hub, according to Raymond Kwok,
vice chairman and managing director of Sun Hung Kai Properties.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the city's office space has been leased out
or sold, he said, noting that this is a very good market response.
</P>
</TEXT>
