<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Global Urban Poverty to Be Held in Florence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- International agencies will
convene a conference in Florence, Italy, next week to discuss the
global urban poverty, the United Nations Office at Geneva (UNOG)
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, entitled "Governance and Participation:
Practical Approaches to Urban Poverty Reduction", will bring
together more than 200 participants representing governments,
local authorities, U.N. agencies, non-governmental organizations,
international aid agencies and research institutions from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
One of the expected outcomes of the conference, scheduled for
November 9-13, UNOG said, is the launching of an international
forum on urban poverty, which is a partnership among
municipalities, bilateral and multilateral support agencies,
private foundations, NGOs and community-based organizations that
are active in the struggle against poverty at the local level.
</P>
<P>
This forum will provide a permanent mechanism for the
discussion of crucial aspects of urban poverty and of the policies
needed to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
The conference, jointly organized by the Nairobi-based United
Nations Center for Human Settlements (HABITAT) and the
Municipality of Florence, is a follow-up to an international
meeting on urban poverty held in Recife, Brazil, in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The conference will enable participants to work towards a
visible framework for urban poverty reduction, based on the Recife
Declaration on Urban Poverty.
</P>
<P>
Focusing on local government as the key factor in the struggle
against urban poverty, the conference will examine the political
role of cities and local authorities, particularly their role as
mediators between the urban poor and central governments.
</P>
<P>
The participants will enter into a "social contract" which will
commit them to reducing and eradicating poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
