<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Describes U.S. Visit as Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said today that his nine-day state visit to the United States was
successful.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first official one ever made by a Chinese head
of state in 12 years, has achieved its objectives of deepening
understanding, broadening common ground, promoting cooperation and
building a future together, said Jiang in an interview with the
China Central Television on his way home.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the visit, which was made as the mankind
are moving toward the 21st century, he and U.S. President Bill
Clinton exchanged views and reached wide-ranging consensus on
bilateral relations and regional and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The two countries pledged in a joint statement to work together
to promote world peace and development and to build a constructive
strategic partnership geared toward the next century, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I also met a wide spectrum of American people,
visited some enterprises, financial institutions, universities and
research institutions, and delivered major speeches in Washington
and New York and at Harvard University."
</P>
<P>
"All these activities afforded me the opportunities to brief
them on the policies on and prospects of China's reform,
opening-up and modernization drive. They helped to deepen the
American people's understanding of China and promote the mutually
beneficial and friendly cooperation between the two countries,"
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese and American people have a long
history of exchanges and traditional friendship and he was deeply
impressed that the American people want to know more about China
and like to see bilateral ties grow from strength to strength.
</P>
<P>
He said he was especially impressed by the initiative and
pragmatic spirit demonstrated by the American people and the great
achievements they have made in the development of high
technologies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that although differences still exist between the two
countries, there is a broad basis for them to develop friendly and
mutually beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that, with the joint efforts of the two
governments and peoples, China-U.S. relations will move forward in
a healthy and stable manner," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president began his nine-day visit on October 26,
which took him to seven American cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
