<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rhee Sets up New Party to Run Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The No. 2 presidential candidate
Rhee In-je formally launched his own political party today, 52
days after he bolted from the ruling New Korea Party (NKP).
</P>
<P>
The New Party by the People (NPP) nominated the former Kyonggi
provincial governor Rhee as its presidential candidate, elected
former House Speaker Lee Man-sup, who recently left the NKP, as
its president and lawmaker Chang Eul-byung as its supreme member.
</P>
<P>
Rhee resigned as Kyonggi governor and left the ruling party in
September to run the presidential election on his own, breaking
his promise to stay in the party after he lost the party's
presidential candidacy to Chairman Lee Hoi-chang in the party's
nomination contest in July.
</P>
<P>
Rhee's continued high popularity and another candidate Lee's
unexpected weak show in the early stages of the presidential race
made it difficult for the loser to give up his presidential
ambition, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"We will achieve authentic national and generational unity
through a change in political generation," Rhee said in his
acceptance speech for the NPP's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
Rhee sharply rebuked the "DJP alliance" between opposition
leaders Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil, calling it a "collusion" to
share power.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration of the NPP is expected to speed up the split
of the ruling party which is in fierce factional feud due to the
continually low approval rate of the party candidate Lee Hoi-chang.
</P>
<P>
The non-mainstream Minju faction, led by President Kim
Young-sam, are pressing Lee Hoi-chang to give up his candidacy,
threatening a collective bolt from the party unless Lee accepts
its demand.
</P>
<P>
As the mainstream Minjong faction led by Lee refuses to bow,
the Minju faction is expected to leave the NKP soon to join the
NPP, to help expand the political clout of its onetime factional
colleague Rhee In-je.
</P>
<P>
Along with the political expansion, the NPP also hopes to
narrow the race down to a two-way competition between Rhee and the
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung, who maintains a solid lead in
various opinion polls, trailed by Rhee and Lee in the second and
third place.
</P>
<P>
With the the coalition of DJP alliance and the low popularity
of former Seoul Mayor Cho Soon, the presidential race is narrowing
to a three-way competition among Kim Dae-jung, Rhee In-je and
ruling party's Lee Hoi-chang.
</P>
<P>
Born in Nonsan, South Chungshong province, the 49-year-old Rhee
was a two-term lawmaker until being elected governor of the
populous Kyonggi Province in the local elections in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer-turned politician, a close associate of President
Kim Young-sam, served as the first Labor Minister under the Kim
Young-sam government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
