<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies He Incited Killing of Rabin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has rejected the charge that he incited the
assassination of former Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, the
Jerusalem Post said today.
</P>
<P>
In an article published on the paper on the occasion of the
second anniversary of Rabin's death, Netanyahu called the murder
"a terrible nightmare" which "produces a primal, wrenching
response, an earthquake of soul."
</P>
<P>
He added that "two years later those memories are still vivid,
and will be with me always."
</P>
<P>
He recalled in the article his acquaintance with Rabin despite
their political rivalry and the shock, disbelief and desperation
he felt when he was informed of Rabin's murder by a radical Jew.
</P>
<P>
On November 4, 1995, Rabin was shot to death in Tel Aviv by
Yigal Amir, a radical Jewish youth, who claimed he had done so to
prevent further handover of land to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Netanyahu, then opposition Likud
leader, was widely blamed for incitement against Rabin and his
government over its peace policies.
</P>
<P>
In his article, Netanyahu expressed the view that the murder of
Rabin was only "a heinous crime by one despicable individual," and
not caused by incitement and campaign rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the leftist camp was making an "unforgivable"
attempt by holding more than half of the population (or the
rightists) the responsibility for the assassination.
</P>
<P>
He described the murder as a "collective guilt' by the whole
nation.
</P>
<P>
Finally, Netanyahu called for an end to political violence,
saying that "We must prevent the recurrence of such a crime. We
must never forget what happened here. We must understand that
violence is an enemy to us all."
</P>
<P>
Israeli peace organizations will hold today a series of
memorial services and demonstrations throughout the country to
remember Rabin and condemn the current Likud government's attempt
to destroy his peace legacy.
</P>
<P>
The rightist camp, however, charged the leftists for taking
advantage of Rabin's murder to spread incitement against the
government and the rightists. 
</P>
