<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Economy Continues Growth: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The economy of Saudi
Arabia has continued its healthy growth throughout the first
nine months of 1997 and indications show that this trend would go
on despite the unstable world oil market situation.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Saudi Monetary Agency Hamad Al-Siari made the
remarks in his annual address before an audience including Saudi
King Fahd and other government officials Monday night, according
to Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that Saudi gross domestic product (GDP) has realized a
growth of 8.6 percent in 1996 and the economy was to maintain the
similar growth rate this year according to preliminary estimates.
</P>
<P>
Al-Siari said Saudi oil revenues, which are still the main
source of state income, would be marginally higher this year than
last year's 11 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the state budget deficit, he said it reduced
from 14.6 percent (of the GDP) in 1992 to only 3.7 percent last
year. He hoped that this down trend would continue for the next
few years to realize a balance in the budget by the end of the
current five year development plan which ends in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Saudi industrial sector other than oil and agricultural
sectors is also expected to maintain a good growth momentum, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the performance of Saudi banks, the governor said they
maintained their exemplary roles in serving the national economy,
 adding that the volume of deposits increased in the first eight
months of this year by an average of 2.6 percent to about 221
billion riyals (58.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
He also noted the marked activity in the Saudi stock market
during the first nine months of this year, saying it witnessed an
increase in the value of traded shares by 186 percent compared
with the corresponding period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the private sector which has been playing an increasing
role in the Saudi economy, Al-Siari said the sector has invested
more and more funds in various government projects and individual
businessmen are urged to mobilize their potentials and resources
in investments which would increase the chances of economic
growth and help in employing national manpower.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Monetary Agency is in charge of monetary matters in
the kingdom and provides the king with an annual report two
months before the issuance of the state budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
