<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversial Housing Project to Move Ahead in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel plans to sell first
1,000 housing units next year in the controversial Har Homa
settlement in the disputed East Jerusalem, a local newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Hebrew daily Haaretz reported in its leading front-page
story that the sale of the first 1,000 Har Homa housing units was
included in the 1998-1999 working plan compiled by Israeli
Construction and Housing Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Israel will build a total of 6,500 housing
units in Har Homa, where the first phase of construction work has
been completed following nearly eight months of non-stop
work. Circular concrete roads and pipelines have been laid around
the Har Homa hill, which was originally covered by pine trees.
</P>
<P>
The Har Homa construction had caused a seven-month freeze in
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which was broken in early
October following the intensive mediation by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Haaretz report was published in coincidence with the
convening of Israeli-Palestinian peace talks in Washington under
the auspices of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) are expected
to conduct serious negotiations on implementing the rest of the
interim agreements as well as on defining the "time-out" of
Israeli settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has been strongly demanding for an end to Israeli
settlement construction, including the Har Homa project, in order
to achieve progress in the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
