<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Economic Targets Not Realized: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Ghana failed to achieve its
macro-economic targets for 1996 except a slight increase in the
gross national product (GNP), an economic study said.
</P>
<P>
The country's GNP had a marginal improvement from five percent
in 1995 to 5.2 percent last year, according to a 156-page report
on the state of Ghana's economy launched recently.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by the Institute of Scientific, Social
and Economic Research, covers topics on international trade and
payments, agricultural services, industrial sectors and inflation
in the country.
</P>
<P>
It revealed that the growth of money supply, which was
targeted at five percent, ended up at 34 percent, while the
budget experienced a deficit of 142 billion cedis rather than a
surplus of 158 billion cedis.
</P>
<P>
The report also touched on some problems facing the economy.
It mentioned, particularly, high inflation and increasing
dollarization of the economy, imbalances between government
expenditures and public revenues, funding of tertiary
institutions and the need for a review of the base year used in
measuring the consumer price index.
</P>
<P>
The report made suggestions in combating these problems and
some projections for this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
