<HEADLINE> Record Price for Chinese Oil Painting at HK Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 4 (Xinhua) -- A painting by a New
York-based Chinese artist, sold for 3.87 million HK dollars (about
500,000 U.S. dollars) here Monday, has set a record auction price
for a Chinese oil painting, according to the auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
"Poppy", which portrays a young woman in traditional Chinese
dress, also became the most expensive piece of works by Chen
Yifei, a Shanghai-educated painter who moved to the United States
in 1980 and quickly gained recognition there.
</P>
<P>
Christie's Hong Kong opened its four-day Autumn auction Monday
with sales of classical and contemporary Chinese paintings and
calligraphy. Some 700 pieces were auctioned for a total of 38.1
million HK dollars (about five million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil painting "Lotus" by renowned artist Wu Guanzhong was sold
for about 1.5 million HK dollars (190,000 U.S. dollars), the
record price for his works of art. Wu, born in 1919, studied oil
painting in France in the 1940s, and established his international
fame in two exhibitions of his traditional Chinese and oil
paintings in San Francisco and London in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"Mountain Landscape" by Zhang Daqian (1899-1983) was sold for
2.22 million HK dollars (280,000 U.S. dollars), one of the highest
prices at the auction.
</P>
<P>
"Water Village", a hand scroll by Mid-14th Century artist Lu
Guang, turned out to be the top selling lot on Monday's auction,
which sold for 2.44 million HK dollars (315,000 U.S. dollar).
Another hand scroll "Joy of Fishing" by Jin Xuan (1361-1436) was
auctioned for 2.33 million HK dollars (300,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sales of masterworks of Chinese arts, Western Jewelry and
jadeite jewelry are going on through Thursday, according to
Christie's Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
