<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> p d s  2434 China-Three Gorges-Economy-1 Three Gorges Project Boosting Chinese Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Claimed as the Chinese
people's most ambitious undertaking after the Great Wall built
more than 2,000 years ago, the Three Gorges Project is expected to
give a fresh boost to the country's economy for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
This view is shared by authoritative Chinese officials and
economists Xinhua has reached.
</P>
<P>
"The Three Gorges Project will become a new point of economic
growth in the Yangtze valley, and in turn prompt the Chinese
economy to maintain the speedy growth in the next century," Li Boxi,
a leading economist with the State Council Development Center, told
Xinhua in an interview today.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze Valley, one of the most prosperous areas in China,
is an axial area in the country's economic layout. It boasts one
third of the national population, and constitutes two fifths of
the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
"China's economic set-up is featured by something like an arrow
on the bowstring, but the arrow, or the Yangtze Valley, was always
in the lack of an adequate impetus to speed ahead," according to
Chen Xuanqing, a State Planning Commission official in charge of
the planning of the nation's economic layout.
</P>
<P>
Since catastrophic floods have frequented the region over the
past 2,000 years, exposing 15 million people on Central China
Plain to an incessant threat and 1.5 million hectares of fields
to the danger of being flooded.
</P>
<P>
Three extremely severe floods in 1930s and 1950s claimed a loss
of 320,000 lives and inundated more than eight million hectares of
cropland along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
An energy shortfall has also hindered the long-term development
of this economic powerhouse of China.
</P>
<P>
However, the Three Gorges Project is expected to spur this
"gigantic arrow of economy", since it will harness the floods on
Yangtze and fully tap the river's abundant hydro-power resources.
</P>
<P>
A huge reservoir with a capacity of 22.15 billion cu m will be
formed behind the mammoth Three Gorges Dam, protecting the areas
along the middle reaches of the Yangtze from the onslaught of
floods.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the world's biggest hydro-power station will also be
built, and it is expected to provide 84.7 billion kwh of clean
electricity annually for the energy-thirsty eastern and central
China, accounting for almost one seventh of the nation's total
hydro-power output in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> p d s  1669 China-Three Gorges-Economy-2 Three Gorges Project Boosting Chinese Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The project will also kick off the full-range development of
the Yangtze's hydro-power resources. The experience drawn from its
construction and the revenues obtained from power generation may
turn the hydro-power resources of 200 million kw inherent in the
Yangtze valley into a real booster of the national economy, when a
chain of hydro-power stations spring up along the upper reaches of
the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
As the leading waterway connecting the coastal and interior
areas, the Yangtze will become a deep-water navigation channel as
the Three Gorges Project is expected to submerge most of the
shoals on its upper reaches, enabling 10,000-ton vessels to sail
from coastal Shanghai all the way up to Chongqing, a newly-founded
municipality in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
"In China's medium- and long-term economic growth strategy, the
Three Gorges will hold a position of immeasurable significance,"
stressed Li Boxi.
</P>
<P>
Located at the confluence of the Yangtze's upper and middle
reaches, the project will serve as an effective link for the
economic chain of coastal, central and the southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "its advantageous situation enables it to convey the
capital, technology and experiences in the coastal region to the
underdeveloped inland areas, thereby speeding up the area's
economic take-off," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xuanqing shared his view by saying that the Three Gorges
Project's decisive role in China's future growth strategy will
turn the Yangtze Valley -- the arrow on the bowstring -- into an
arrow ready to set off and effect an economy take-off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
