<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transport Services in Eritrea Make Big Headway: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean Minister of
Transport and Communications Saleh Idris Kekia has said transport
services at home and communications with outside world have made
significant headway since 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of English weekly "Eritrea
Profile" available here today, the remarks were made by the
Eritrean minister at a meeting in Asmara, capital of Eritrea
recently.
</P>
<P>
He said, a project aimed at rehabilitating the port of Massawa
and modernizing the port of Assab at a cost of about eight
million U.S. Dollars has already been prepared in cooperation
with the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
There are also plans to set up a container terminal in the
port of Assab, he added.
</P>
<P>
The work of placing light houses in Eritrean islands in a bid
to ensuring the safety of ships inside the Eritrean water
territory is being carried out and is expected to be completed by
the coming year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to five airline companies operating in Eritrea, the
minister said, "although establishing our own airlines company
demands tremendous amount of money and great skill, we are trying
to work in shares with other foreign companies."
</P>
<P>
He said, various tasks aimed at developing air transport in
Eritrea and upgrading the Asmara International Airport are going
out well, adding that a new commercial airport that would
facilitate the process of making Massawa an economic zone is
being built there.
</P>
<P>
On the land transport in the country, the minister said the
number of buses rose from 260 to more than 1,300. "This changed
the service of public transportation, and today there is almost
no place in Eritrea where buses do not reach," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the progress in telecommunications, the minister
said the Eritrean Telecommunications Authority introduced a
digital system that enabled its clients to reach the outside
world directly.
</P>
<P>
"All of the Eritrean bigger towns will have a telephone line
that links them to each other and to the external world, and this
is expected to be completed by 2000," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
