<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Liberalize Tea Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Tea Development
Authority (KTDA) has announced that its liberalization program is
on schedule in a bid to promote tea production of the country.
</P>
<P>
KTDA Managing Director Eustace Karanja said here Monday that
"liberalization means empowerment of the farmers to participate
in all important financial and operational decisions regarding
their factory companies," according to a Kenya Times report
today.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the authority is in the process of
completing administrative modalities to enable farmers to
effectively acquire ownership of their factories or companies
through allotment and purchase of share equity.
</P>
<P>
"This process will soon be completed and every grower will be
allotted shares under an already formulated procedure," Karanja
added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the authority merely manages the companies and
provides necessary loans for establishment of new factories and
expansion of existing ones.
</P>
<P>
The KTDA will no longer determine and announce rates of
payments to tea farmers from next year.
</P>
<P>
He announced at a press conference that KTDA had released 5.6
billion Kenyan Shillings (about 90 million U.S. Dollars) as
second bonus payment to tea farmers in the country.
</P>
<P>
The managing director stated that the green leaf production
for the crop year 1996/97 dropped to 522,132 tons from 610,706
tons in previous year due to the drought suffered in major tea
producing areas.
</P>
<P>
The drop in production has been compensated by better prices
of tea owing to a more favorable exchange rate with the crop
year's annual average green leaf payment increasing to 15.32
Shillings per kilogram from 13.22 Shillings in previous crop
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
