<HEADLINE> Kaunda Not to Return Home Until Early December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
lUSAKA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian president, now
the leader of the opposition United National Independence Party
(UNIP) Kenneth Kaunda will not return home until early December,
his son said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Wezi Kaunda as saying that his
father will be on a month-long marathon tour which will finally
end in the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said his father was not fleeing from the October 28
attempted coup as it is being speculated.
</P>
<P>
"Dr Kaunda's trip abroad has nothing to do with the situation
at home. In fact these invitations have been long standing dating
as far back as a month ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview from Zimbabwean capital Harare
Monday, Kaunda told the post that he has numerous commitments
between now and December and will only be free to return home in
the first week of December.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda told the Zambian newspaper, the Post, that "tell the
MMD (the ruling Movement for Multi-Party Democracy) that they now
know when i am coming back, if they want to arrest me, they can
do so when i return."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who went to Lesotho a few days before the coup to have
attended the coronation of King Letsie iii on October 31, will
hold lectures at a number of universities in London.
</P>
<P>
He will also attend a Gandhi conference in Bombay and another
for the World Federation of Peace in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
