<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urges Iraq to Rescind Ban on Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has urged Iraq to
back down from its ban on U.S. citizens in the United Nations
weapons inspection team, local newspapers and radios reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Making the call, Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah was also quoted
as saying that the Kuwaiti armed forces are on alert to ward off
what might result from the current Iraq-U.S. standoff.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the current crisis will not develop into
a full confrontation between Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah also called on Iraq "to comply with and implement all
the U.N. Security Council resolutions and stop challenging the
international community."
</P>
<P>
Iraq last Wednesday decided to turn back the 10 U.S. inspectors
working with the U.N. Special Commission for eliminating Iraq's
mass destructive weapons, and has refused twice the entry of three
U.S. inspectors on the following days.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. called Iraq's decision "unacceptable" and said all
options are open to force Iraq to back away.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's ban on U.S. inspectors was announced after the
U.N. Security Council, in a U.S.-led campaign, passed a resolution
to threaten more sanctions to press for Iraq's cooperation with
U.N. inspectors. Indefinite sanctions were imposed seven years
ago after the Gulf War triggered off by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
