<HEADLINE> Israel's Tourism Drops Dramatically in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's tourism suffered a
six percent decrease during August in the number of visitors
compared to the same period a year ago, today's The Jerusalem
Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The unstable security situation, linked to the stalled Middle
East peace process, has been attributed to the setback of the
tourism.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Tourism Ministry as saying that a total
of 202,300 foreign visitors entered the country during August in
comparison with last year's 215,200 tourists in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Hotel Association economic adviser Pnina Ben-David said
the situation is worse than the ministry's statistics reveal.
</P>
<P>
Based on hotel stays by foreign tourist, Ben-David said that
in the first eight months of the year, tourism dropped by 8 to 9
percent compared to the previous year. He noted that "We still
can not see the light at the end of the tunnel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
