<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Yet to Take Stand on Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait still has not taken
an official stand as to whether to take part in the controversial
Middle East and North Africa (MENA) economic conference scheduled
to be held in Doha, Qatar on November 16-18.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad said after a parliamentary meeting Monday night
that "the government of Kuwait has not yet responded to the
invitation it has received from the Qatari government."
</P>
<P>
"We have received an invitation to attend, but we have not
replied so far," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari ambassador in Kuwait delivered Sunday to Sheikh
Sabah an official invitation from Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh
Hamad Bin Jassim Bin Jabir Al-Thani to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after a regular weekly cabinet meeting
Sunday night also did not mention Kuwait's stand on the Doha
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries have expressed their intention to boycott
the meeting, which Israel is expected to participate.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, two members of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) which also includes Kuwait, Oman,
Bahrain and Qatar, have said they would boycott the conference.
</P>
<P>
But Qatar insists on holding the annual gathering although it
has downgraded it from a summit to a ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Chamber of Commerce and Industry announced Saturday
that it would officially boycott the economic conference although
all Kuwaiti businessmen could attend the meeting as individuals.
</P>
<P>
The chamber's announcement was made three days after Saudi
Arabian Chamber of Commerce and Industry made a similar decision
to boycott the conference by all Saudi private sector
businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
