<HEADLINE> 35,000 Kenyans Die of Environmentally-related </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. official has
said some 35,000 Kenyans die of environmentally-related disease
and about 37,000 children under the age of five die from
malnutrition every day, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Reuben Olenbo, Deputy Executive Director of the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP), was quoted as saying that the
environmental degradation has affected human activities such as
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He told a regional workshop on environmental education in
eastern and southern Africa Monday that sea level rise has
threatened the lives of three billion people, about 60 percent of
the world population.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official noted that UNEP has started a program of
"Global Environmental Citizenship Program" to promote
environmental education in various parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to create public awareness on dangers
of environmental degradation and give alternative solutions to
the problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
Olembo pointed out that the program would require all
countries to change their strategies on environmental management
and redesign approaches to communication and production of
learning and teaching materials.
</P>
<P>
He urged universities and academic institutions throughout the
world to design programs which have a bearing on lives of the
grass-roots people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
