<HEADLINE> Asian Finance Officials to Meet on Asian Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputy finance ministers and
central bankers from Asian-Pacific countries will gather here on
November 18-19 to discuss the creation of an Asian fund to cope
with the current currency crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Philippine Finance Department confirmed today
that deputy finance ministers from the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN), Japan and the United States will be invited
to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank, the
Asian Development Bank and countries that contributed to the IMF's
bailout fund for Thailand will also be represented at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Proposals for a fund of some kind to aid Asian countries facing
financial difficulties have been discussed for several months
since the regional currency crisis began in early July.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Southeast Asian countries proposed establishing such
a fund during September's meetings of the IMF and the World Bank
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF has warned against the projected fund, saying it
could undercut conditions attached to its economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said on Monday
that the proposed Asian bailout fund should be supported by the
IMF and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said the result of the discussions on the fund will be
presented to the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation summit meeting
scheduled for November 24-25 in Vancouver, Canada.  
</P>
</TEXT>
