<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Sanyo Securities Goes Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Sanyo Securities Co.,
plagued by massive bad loans, declared insolvent Monday when it
sought to reorganize itself under the country's law, press reports
here said today.
</P>
<P>
The second-tier brokerage, with 373.6 billion yen (about 3.1
billion U.S. dollars) worth of uncollectible debts incurred by
affiliated non-bank financial institutions, became the first listed
brokerage house to file for reorganization under the Corporate
Rehabilitation Law.
</P>
<P>
The action, filed with the Tokyo District Court, was tantamount
to a declaration of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The brokerage house decided Monday to suspend some operations,
Sanyo Securities President Takashi Ikeuchi told a press conference
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Ikeuchi also said that all 21 of the company's top executives
submitted their letters of resignation to take responsibility for
the failure.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo District Court, which now has full control of the
brokerage house's assets, approved special treatment of clients'
assests to ensure their complete protection.
</P>
<P>
Under this allowance, Sanyo's clients will be free to withdraw
money from their accounts with the brokerage.
</P>
<P>
Sanyo said it took the action because its regular business
operations would be jeopardized by its decision to take legal
steps to liquidate its troubled non-bank affiliates.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Sanyo failed to meet a deadline for its repayment of
loans totaling 20 billion yen (about 167 million dollars) from
Nippon Life Insurance Co. and eight other life insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
The brokerage house requested a deferment of the repayment in a
effort to improve its financial situation, but it had to abandon
its plan after the life insurance firms rejected the request.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the brokerage's crash, Koji Omi, Director General
of Japan's Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said today that he is
worried that the collapse of Sanyo Securities Co. will hurt the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of Sanyo Securities will have some psychologically
negative effects on the economy," the EPA head said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Records Vigorous Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has recorded vigorous economic growth in recent years due to the
rapid development of an export-oriented economy and efforts to
develop international markets.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of 1996 show the province had used
foreign funds of 22.3 billion U.S. dollars, with over 2,000
foreign-funded projects involving investments of over 10 million
U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The province recorded an average annual foreign trade growth
rate of 34.6 percent over the past five years. Foreign trade has
emerged as a major sector promoting rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
Exports of machinery and electronics products jumped by 30
percent in 1996, with exports in primary agricultural and sideline
products falling by 7.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
A number of development zones have been opened in the province,
including 11 national and 67 provincial level zones. The province
had invested 23 billion yuan (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) in zone
construction by the end of March this year.
</P>
<P>
The zones, which cover at total of 200 sq.km., have approved
over 21,900 projects involving foreign investments of 8.43 billion
U.S. dollars. A total of 23,300 enterprises have entered
operations, including 2,274 foreign-funded ventures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
