<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Malaysia to Hold Talks on Gas Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Malaysia will hold
talks later this week over the impact of the current regional
currency crisis on the price of gas to be produced from the two
countries' joint development area (JDA), Thai Industry Ministry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sivavong Cangkasiri, former permanent secretary of the Thai
Industry Ministry and co-chairman of the Malaysia-Thailand Joint
Authority will meet with his Malaysian counterpart in Malaysia to
discuss the impact of currency devaluation on the agreed-upon
price for JDA gas, a local newspaper today quoted a senior
official of the Industry Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official said that although Thailand and Malaysia agreed in
late September on a price of JDA gas at 2.3 U.S. dollars for one
million British thermal units, the recent turmoil in Southeast
Asian currencies required the two parties to review the contract
to prevent a possible dispute in the future, as the Thai baht has
depreciated differently from the Malaysian ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysia-Thailand Joint Authority is a statutory body set
up in 1990 by the two governments to govern the exploration and
production of petroleum resources in the JDA.
</P>
<P>
Estimated to have a gas reserve of over 10,000 billion cubic
feet, the JDA fields are expected to turn out at least 600 million
cubic feet of gas per day by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
