<HEADLINE> 2 Russian Banks to Open Subsidiaries in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 4 (Xinhua) -- India will provide licenses
to two Russian major commercial banks to open full-fledged
branches in the country in a bid to enhance their mutual trade
ties, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Income Bank of Russia (IBR), which has already opened its
representative office in India, is likely to be permitted shortly
to upgrade its status in New Delhi to a subsidiary. The other
Russian commercial bank has also been cleared to open its office
in India.
</P>
<P>
Both India and Russia have decided to improve their banking
arrangements to bolster bilateral trade, as insufficient banking
facilities are considered to be a major obstacle standing in the
way of development of the two countries' economic relations, the
same official said.
</P>
<P>
In return, Russia has agreed to provide licenses to two Indian
banks for opening their subsidiaries in Moscow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Heads off Pension Rush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government today moved
quickly to head off an expected wave of pension applications by
those eager to retire before a pension reform program kicks off.
</P>
<P>
Issuing an emergency decree, the government froze all new
pension demands until the reform goes into effect with the passage
of next year's budget bill through the country's parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the freeze, which applies to both private and public
sectors, will not affect pension requests made before today.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget, due to be approved by the end of the year,
includes 4.1 trillion lire, equivalent to about 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars, of spending cuts in the national pension system.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was reached between the government and trade
unions on Saturday after five months of talks.
</P>
<P>
The document raises the minimum retirement age in the private
sector from 53 to 54 next year, provided the worker has 35 years
of service. It will then gradually be raised to 57.
</P>
<P>
Blue-collar workers are exempted from the changes under an
agreement with the Communist Refoundation party.
</P>
<P>
The deal will also bring public and private sectors into line
by 2004, eliminating many public-sector perks, and will freeze
30,000 early-retirement applications by teachers until 1999.
</P>
<P>
Crucial for improving Italy's fiscal performance, savings from
the plan are expected to help secure its qualification for entry
into the European Monetary Union (EMU) slated for 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
