<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Seeks to Cooperate with Japan in Nuclear Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Ministry of Energy
would like to cooperate with Japan in the development of fast
neutron reactor technology, ministry spokesman Kaurov said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed during a meeting in Krasnoyarsk on
November 1-2 to cooperate in the nuclear sector.
</P>
<P>
Kaurov said the fast neutron reactor, a technology which Japan
has not grasped yet, represents the best direction for the
development of nuclear power in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Russia suggests that Japan arrange financing for a BN-800 new
motor unit for a neutron reactor. In return, Russian would
transfer its fast neutron reaction technology, which has a good
reputation for safety.
</P>
<P>
Russia is considering setting up the motor units at nuclear
power plants located in Beloyarsk or the Yuzhny Ural.
</P>
<P>
Although Japan has advanced the nuclear power industry, the
supply for its nuclear fuels is monopolized by the United
States. Russia also wants to become a supplier of nuclear fuels to
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customers Rush to Closed Banks in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Security, police and army officers have strengthened their
presence at all offices of the banks in the wake of possible mass
riots, while immigration authorities imposed a travel ban on 60
senior bank executives.
</P>
<P>
Customers of the closed banks in other cities also went to
local branches to ask for their savings. They were worried that
they would be unable to obtain their money from the banks.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government Saturday announced the closure of 16
banks as part of its efforts to revitalize the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The government said the closed banks were insolvent to the
point of endangering business continuity, disturbing the overall
banking system, and harming the interests of the society.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the public from being panic, Bank Indonesia has
promised 2.3 trillion rupiah (about 657.14 million U.S. dollar) to
help pay minor depositors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government said it would continue paying the
salaries of bank employees who have lost their jobs in the closed
banks for three months. The government also pledged to help the
employees find new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
