<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Rises on Intervention, Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah rose 8
percent against the U.S. dollar in hectic trading Monday due to
what many believe as positive reaction to wide-ranging economic
reforms announced by the government and joint intervention by
foreign central banks.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah surged to a high of 3,240 against the greenback
before closing at 3,270/3,300, compared with an opening of
3,540/3,555, dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad said Monday in a statement
that there was a concerted effort by Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, and Singapore and Japanese central banks to support the
rupiah.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say what form of intervention was taken by
the three banks.
</P>
<P>
"The concerted effort was aimed at strengthening the rupiah to
levels more appropriate with the fundamentals of the Indonesian
economy," Mar'ie said.
</P>
<P>
He said the joint effort would contribute positively to the
implementation of the reform package announced by the Indonesian
government recently.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform package, the government will further trim its
budget spending, abolish monopolies in several food commodities
and liquidate insolvent banks.
</P>
<P>
The package had gained support from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank. The IMF
has agreed to provide 23 billion U.S. dollars in financial and
technical aid to Indonesia to cope with its monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent against the U.S.
dollar since the beginning of this year. It was badly hit by the
monetary crisis in Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
