<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urumqi Residents Breathe Clean Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The switch from the use of coal
to natural gas has enabled more than one million people in Urumqi,
the capital of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,
to breathe cleaner air.
</P>
<P>
The switch, which ended the city's long history of burning
coal, is regarded as a great contribution to improving the living
standards of local residents and improving the urban environment.
</P>
<P>
Urumqi means "beautiful pastureland" in the Mongolian
language. However, the city was subject to serious air pollution
for an extended period due to the use of coal, combined with
unique local geological and climatic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The city government launched a major gas supply project to
improve the urban environment, with the effort centering on the
building of a 300 kilo meter pipe-line linking the city with
Turpan-Hami Oil Field.
</P>
<P>
The project, completed at a cost of 480 million yuan (60
million US dollars), provides 600 million cu.m. of gas annually
and easily fulfills the local demand for gas.
</P>
<P>
The Turpan-Hami Basin, located in the eastern part of Xinjiang,
has over 26 billion cu.m. of proven gas reserves. Urumqi has a
population of 1.4 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss President to Visit Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Swiss President Arnold Koller
is scheduled to visit Thailand on November 17 to boost cooperation
between the two countries, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Koller will be the first Swiss president to officially visit
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Switzerland and Thailand will sign a treaty
on the transfer of prisoners and an agreement on the promotion and
protection of investments, deputy Foreign Ministry spokesman
Thinnakorn Kannasutra was quoted today by local press reports as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is listed as Thailand's 19th largest trading
partner. Last year, bilateral trade between the two countries
totaled 195.7 million U.S. dollars, with Thailand suffering a
trade deficit of about 509 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, Switzerland enjoyed a trade
surplus of about 94 million dollars with Thailand. 
</P>
