<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The following major economic
news briefs were reported in Latin American countries in the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's wine exports jumped to 303.6 million U.S.
dollars in the first nine months of 1997, a 50.5 percent increase
over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Agricultural Policies and Studies said wine
exports rose from 126.4 million liters in January-September 1996
to 152.9 million liters in the same period this year.
</P>
<P>
Price per liter rose from 1.19 U.S. dollars to 1.97 this year.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will import more rice from Argentina and
Uruguay in the next crop season due to a shortage in domestic
production.
</P>
<P>
Brazil will buy 1.2 million tons of rice during the period of
March 1997-February 1998.
</P>
<P>
Rice production in Brazil will amount to 10.9 million tons for
the next year, while domestic consumption is expected to be 11.7
million tons.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Beef exports rose by 0.5 percent in
Brazil in the first three quarters of 1997, compared with
the same period last year, the Industrialized Beef Exporters
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The association said exports amounted to 311 million dollars
in the first nine months.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Finance Ministry of Costa Rica will issue 187
billion colons (779 million dollars) of bonds to pay the interest
on domestic debts and finance political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO -- The German automobile maker Volkswagen increased its
sales in Mexico by 40 percent during the first nine months of 1997
compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
The German automobile company said they sold 47,540 vehicles in
the country to meet Mexico's demands. During the first three
quarters, Vokswagen made up 23.1 percent of the total Mexican
automobile market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
