<HEADLINE> Budgetary Funding Short of Educational Needs in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's budgetary funding
for education will be about 1.79 billion U.S. dollars short of the
sector's needs in 1998, a congressional group has said.
</P>
<P>
The educational sector needs an equivalent of 5.56 billion
dollars to keep the system running, said a sub-committee of the
Chamber of Deputies, or the lower house of the National Congress.
</P>
<P>
However, the sub-committee on education, science and technology
and culture financing noted, the 1998 budget bill proposed by the
government allows only 3.77 billion dollars for education programs.
</P>
<P>
Although the appropriation, if granted, appears to be 15.6
percent more than 1997, the increase is likely to be written off
by inflation, said Rodrigo Cabezas, the sub-committee's chairman.
</P>
<P>
What makes it worse, Cabezas said, is that the education
system's deficit this year will be transferred into next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
