<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Between Romania and Russia Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Romania and
Russia has declined markedly since the disintegration of the
Council for Mutual Economic Assistance (COMECON), a Russian trade
representative in Romania told Rompres today.
</P>
<P>
Mark Abarsalin, Russian trade representative in the Russian
embassy in Bucharest, said bilateral trade between the two
countries dropped to 1.6 billion U.S. dollars last year from 5
billion in 1989.
</P>
<P>
In the economic and trade exchanges between the two countries,
Romania exported only 200 million U.S. dollars in goods to Russia
last year, while imports from Russia were 1.4 billion, 90 percent
of which was material, natural gas and crude oil, Abarsalin said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that other East European countries exported to
Russia much more than Romania, although Romania is the only
country that enjoys a 25 percent taxation remit in its export to
Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
