<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Fish Output Near Target in First 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's production of fish
species came near to the annual target in the first six months of
the present 1997-98 fiscal year beginning April, registering a 93
percent performance, official paper The New Light of Myanmar today
quoted a senior livestock and fisheries official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here Monday reviewing the work done, U
Aung Thaung, Minister for Livestock and Fisheries, disclosed that
sales of fish species of the department overfulfilled the annual
target by 64 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
He added that production of freshwater larvae constituted 60
percent while that of sea larvae registered 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exploited about 590,000 tons of marine products
annually in the past few years with the maximum sustainable yield
estimated at about 1.05 million tons per year.
</P>
<P>
Production of freshwater fish and that of marine fish in the
country registered an annual growth rate of 8.9 and 39.5 percent
respectively in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March.
</P>
<P>
Total export of the livestock and fishery sector in the fiscal
reached 121 million U.S. dollars with fish and prawn as the major
export items.  
</P>
</TEXT>
