<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Group Meets in Dhaka Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of donor
countries and agencies of the Bangladesh Aid Group today began a
meeting here to discuss Bangladesh's socio-economic development
and future action plans to achieve faster growth and
macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being held in Dhaka for the first time in 25
years instead of at the traditional venue of Paris.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government will present to the meeting a paper
on its achievements in economic, social and infrastructure
development which highlights the thrust on programs like poverty
alleviation and infrastructure development that need more foreign
aid and investment.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the Bangladeshi government is planning to
seek more than 2.1 billion U.S. dollars of fresh aid commitment by
the donors for food, commodity and development projects in the
current financial year starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was presided over by World Bank Vice
President for South Asia Region Ms. Mieko Nishimizu.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Minister of Finance S.A.M.S. Kibria is to make a
statement at the meeting, which will focus on major economic
indicators and basics like export earnings, revenue collection,
remittance, aid disbursement, credit expansion, foreign reserves,
loan realization, privatization and the banking sector's reform.
</P>
<P>
Later, the representative of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) in Dhaka will present an overview on Bangladesh's
macro-economic situation and its growth prospects by the end of
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has six working sessions covering the country's
macro-economic situation and future action program for economic
and social development. Discussions will be held on human
development, social aspects, food security and private sector
development. After the discussions, the donors will consider fresh
aid to the poor South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The Aid Group meeting will be followed by an investors'
conference on the prospects of investment opportunities in
Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
