<HEADLINE> Shanghai Witnesses Tourism Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
metropolitan area, hosted over 1.2 million foreign tourists in the
first nine months of this year, a year-on-year rise of 18.4
percent, with earnings growing by 16.6 percent to 980 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 million Chinese tourists visited the city during the
period, a level equal to the total for 1996, with related earnings
hitting a record 40 billion yuan (4.819 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Municipal tourism officials attributed the success, at least in
part, to improved coordination between tourism, transportation,
commerce, cultural and other relevant departments.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Shanghai called for all concerned sectors to
engage in a concerted effort to improve the efficiency of tourism.
</P>
<P>
Said efforts included the addition of new air routes and
tourist trains, according to municipal officials.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai offers regularly scheduled air flights to 88 Chinese
and foreign cities and has opened special train routes to major
tourist areas such as Suzhou, Hangzhou, Wuxi, Nanjing and Mount
Huangshan.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between cultural and commercial departments have
led to the establishment of a series of tourism festivals
featuring films, the tea culture, local fruit and trade,
attracting an ever increasing number of tourists.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have led to the creation of new tourism programs
related to sports, exhibitions, and tours of major industrial
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
