<HEADLINE> Aviation Sector Turns to Home Mart for Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese civil aviation
companies are turning now to the domestic capital market to fund
their stout growth, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
China Eastern Airlines, the country's first A share in the
civil aviation sector, will make its debut tomorrow in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai-based company issued 300 million domestic A shares
last month at 2.45 yuan (about 0.3 U.S.dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Airlines has decided to issue 17.53 million A shares
before the end of this year and Air China, the country's largest
aviation company, will also go public both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
It is reported Shenzhen Airport and Hongqiao Airport are
considering going public domestically.
</P>
<P>
Experts said many aviation companies have high
assets-to-liability ratios and going public is an effective way to
level off the ratio.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Administration of China is exploring various
domestic fund-raising channels to pool funds to meet the surging
capital demand aroused by the industry's robust growth.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the A-share market, corporate bonds,
construction bonds and convertible bonds are also under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the sector said enterprises in the industry will
conduct direct fund-raising, such as the issue of shares and
bonds, more frequently while reducing indirect fund-raising
activities, including using bank loans and leasing.
</P>
<P>
The civil aviation sector is set to maintain a 15 percent
annual growth rate and a total of 100 billion yuan (about 12
billion U.S. dollars) will be invested to improve infrastructure
and build about 40 airports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
