<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Grant Legal Protection to Visiting Filipino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and the United
States have concluded an agreement granting Filipino troops legal
protection while conducting military exercises in American
territory.
</P>
<P>
The Legal Framework for Filipino Personnel Temporarily Visiting
the U.S. under the Mutual Defense Treaty was part of a package for
the early conclusion of a new Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA)
between the two countries, local newspaper Manila Standard
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"There is already a legal framework (for the protection of
visiting Filipino troops)," the report quoted Philippine Foreign
Secretary Domingo Siazon as saying.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said the just-concluded agreement was formulated as an
executive order so as not to require ratification by the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Manila and Washington are trying to wrap up a new SOFA, which
will facilitate the conduct of joint exercises between Filipino
and American military personnel, to improve Philippine-U.S.
military relations.
</P>
<P>
The country's previous SOFA with the U.S. was based on the
Military Bases Agreement, which the Philippine Senate scrapped in
1991.
</P>
<P>
However, Siazon declined to comment on the details of the
agreement, saying only it "will be signed simultaneously (with the
new SOFA)."
</P>
<P>
"We have already agreed to giving limited immunity to Filipino
troops going there (United States)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines proposed early in the negotiations that
Filipino troops be granted the same privileges their American
counterparts enjoy while conducting military exercises in the
Philippines, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. panel shot down the proposal and came up with the
just-concluded agreement, which is similar to the one Washington
has with Israel, providing for the legal protection of Filipino
troops visiting the U.S. for military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Previously, reciprocity and jurisdiction over cases committed
by American soldiers while in the Philippines for military
exercises were two major issues during the SOFA negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-third of China's Farmland to Use Water-Saving Irrigation Methods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Water-saving irrigation, deemed
a fundamental way out of China's drought problem, is expected to
be adopted for use on one-third of the country's farmland next
year.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily announced the ambitious plan by quoting
Vice-Minister of Water Resources Zhang Chunyuan.
</P>
<P>
Next year, he said, water-saving irrigation systems operating
through a pipeline network and other practical measures, such as
protection against serious leaking from ditches, will be
introduced into 16.3 million hectares that grow grain and cotton.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 10 billion cubic meters of water will be
saved next year and 10 billion more kilograms of grain will be
produced when the entire plan is completed.
</P>
<P>
It means that by the end of next year, experts say water-saving
irrigation systems will be applied to more than 35 million
hectares, more than one-third of China's farmland. China has about
100 million hectares of farmland, though the State's latest survey
indicated the figure is more than 120 million hectares but has not
been verified by land authorities.
</P>
<P>
Eleven billion yuan ($1.3 billion) has been poured into the
program, of which about one-third of the investment came from bank
loans approved by the State with lower interest rates as financing
subsidies, 25 percent were from local governments and the rest
raised by famers.
</P>
<P>
Zhang quoted climate forecasts as saying farms will face
serious water shortages through this winter and next spring
because less precipitation is expected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
