<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Invalidates Old Identity Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has invalidated old
identity cards issued before December 31, 1973 and called on all
holders to renew them.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Registration of Persons Department (RPD)
today was quoted by local press as saying that all national
identity cards issued before that date had been canceled and
holders should apply for renewals.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 80 percent of those holders have renewed their
identity cards, the spokesman said. The department requires the
rest holders to renew their cards soon.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the government canceled ID cards
throughout the nation, according to a well-informed local source.
</P>
<P>
The source disclosed that the government has discovered many
fake ID cards these years.
</P>
<P>
Some of the fake cards were forged and held by rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), posing a security threat
to the government, he added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting an ethnic war for an independent
state of their own in the north and east of the country since
1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
