<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beverage Hygiene Up; Tableware Still Unsatisfying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- The quality of soft drinks sold
in the Chinese market has greatly improved, but the hygiene of the
tableware in public eating places is not so satisfying, a national
inspection indicated.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health announced the results of the inspection
yesterday to start a week-long promotion for the Food Hygiene Law,
which went into effect in October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Three varieties of soft drinks, tableware detergents,
disinfectants and also the hygiene of tableware at eating places
were inspected in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The results indicated that 98.2 percent of the drinks
containing lactic acid, 98 percent of the carbonic acid drinks and
84.5 percent of the plant protein drinks meet the national
standard.
</P>
<P>
Bacteria contamination and insufficient protein are major
factors that affected the quality of soft drinks, said Kan Xuegui,
department director in charge of health inspection for the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,632 restaurants and roadside food stands were
inspected, and only 44.4 percent satisfied the State requirement
on tableware disinfection.
</P>
<P>
About 68 percent of the tableware inspected met the national
standard after disinfection. Of the tableware detergents
inspected, 92.1 percent met the standard.
</P>
<P>
All the units and individuals that failed to meet the national
standards have been handled by local health departments in line
with the Food Hygiene Law, Kan said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that local health departments should step up
inspections at roadside food stands and, in the meantime, increase
publicity and education to ensure good public health.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
