<HEADLINE> Private Firms Can Help State's Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- China's private firms should
play a role in the State sector's restructuring, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, chairman of All-China Federation of Industry and
Commerce (ACFIC), said non-State firms could participate in the
State companies' reorganization in various ways, which include
running them under contract, leasing them or establishing joint
ventures or shareholding co-operative firms with them.
</P>
<P>
Jing said at ACFIC's Eighth Congress, which opened yesterday in
Beijing, that China's private sector, which was upgraded from "a
supplemental part of the national economy" to "a significant
constituent of the national economy" in the country's economic
theory during the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China, is facing an unprecedented development opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, the private sector is taken into the
country's economic system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jing said that labour-extensive enterprises in the private
sector should try to create more jobs for laid-off workers to ease
the employment pressure from the reshuffle of the State firms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he encouraged the private business people to step
into technology-intensive business and establish themselves in the
world market.
</P>
<P>
He urged private business people to pay special attention to
agriculture, saying they should contribute to the
industrialization of the country's agriculture by investing more
money and enlisting advanced technology and management techniques
to develop the field.
</P>
<P>
Citing the private firms' average registered capital of 500,000
yuan (60,000 U.S. dollars) and 14 employees each, Jing said most
of the private companies are still weak. Their management
philosophies are generally out of date, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
