<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-third of China's Farmland To Use Water-saving Methods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Water-saving irrigation, deemed
a fundamental way out of China's drought problem, is expected to
be adopted for use on one-third of the country's farmland next
year, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Water Resources Zhang Chunyun announced such
an ambitious plan yesterday at a national working conference on
water-saving irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Next year, Zhang said, water-saving irrigation systems
operating through a pipeline network and other practical measures,
such as protection against serious leaking from ditches, will be
introduced into 16.3 million hectares that grow grain and cotton.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 10 billion cubic metres of water will be
saved next year and 10 billion more kilograms of grain will be
produced when the entire plan is completed.
</P>
<P>
It means that by the end of next year, experts say water-saving
irrigation systems will be applied to more than 35 million
hectares, more than one-third of China's farmland.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, water-saving irrigation methods, including
modern spray and drip irrigation techniques, and various practical
seepage-proof measures used in open-cut trenches built decades ago
have been applied to 19 million hectares across 300
drought-stricken countries in North China.
</P>
<P>
Eleven billion yuan (1.3 billion U.S. dollars) has been poured
into the programme, of which about one-third of the investment
came from the bank loans approved by the State with lower interest
rates as financing subsidies, 25 percent were from local
governments and the rest raised by rural residents.
</P>
<P>
Zhang quoted climate forecasts as saying farms will face
serious water shortages through this winter and next spring
because less precipitation is expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
