<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Cut Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank is
planning to reduce lending rates following an across-the-board
drop in the yields of Treasury Bills (T-bills) on Monday's auction
by the Bureau of Treasury.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's weekly T-bills auction, yields for the
benchmark 91-day bills plunged by 86.3 basis points to 16.341
percent from last week's 17.204 percent.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted by local
newspaper Manila Bulletin as saying that he would recommend to the
Monetary Board, the policy-making body of the bank, corresponding
reduction in its overnight repurchase paper when it meets
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank charges about 16.125 percent on its overnight
lending rate and 12 percent on its borrowing rate.
</P>
<P>
Singson indicated that he would also recommend "corresponding
adjustments" in the yields of other lending instruments such as
the three-month reverse repurchase papers which now stand at
16.125 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Monetary Board may ease up the stringent
conditions attached to the central bank's lending facility on
condition that the money lent out would not be used by banks for
speculation in foreign exchange market, Singson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
