<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Fisheries Attract Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, November 4 (Xinhua) -- A constantly increasing number
of foreign investors have tasted success after investing in the
fisheries sector in Dalian, a major coastal city in northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The city had approved over 1,600 foreign-funded rural
enterprises in the sector by the end of last year, with total
foreign investments standing at 1.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Related ventures recorded a total export volume of over 12
billion yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local planting and breeding sectors have attracted increasing
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented enterprises currently contribute 60 percent of
local foreign exchange earnings from agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
The achievements can be attributed to favorable geographical
conditions, as well as the introduction of a series of policies
designed to encourage the use of overseas funding for the
development of local agriculture and fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The city is currently home to over 6,000 foreign-funded
enterprises, involving foreign funds of over 10 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city's four major economic zones focus on forestry, fruit
orchards, animal husbandry, grain production, fisheries, nonstaple
foodstuffs and vegetables. These zones have greatly promoted the
coordinated development of the local economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
