<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Reiterates Support for Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The White House said Monday
affirmative action needs to be kept as a corrective tool against
discrimination and racism despite a Supreme Court decision that
rejects challenge to California affirmative action ban.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court today let stand California's Proposition 209,
which bans affirmative action for minorities and women by any
level of state or city government. A coalition of civil rights
groups had asked the court to hear arguments they hoped would
overturn the California law, but the justices rejected that move.
</P>
<P>
At today's press briefing White House spokesman Mike McCurry
reiterated Clinton's support for affirmative action programs,
saying the administration's views of Prop 209 are well known and
articulated by the president.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton "has very clearly stated, over and over
again, that we need to keep that as a corrective tool to protect
Americans who have suffered injustice, discrimination and even the
residue of racism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
