<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Personal Incomes Gain Moderately in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The personal incomes in the
U.S. increased moderately and the spending also moderated in
September, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that personal incomes rose 0.4 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.94 trillion dollars following
a 0.6 percent increase in August.
</P>
<P>
Personal consumption spending also increased a small 0.2
percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.54 trillion
dollars in the month. That followed gains of 0.3 percent in August
and 1.1 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Wages and salaries -- the largest component of income -- rose
0.3 percent in September, and transfer payments such as Social
Security and welfare increased 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists said personal income gains reflect steady wage
increases stemming from tight labor markets favoring job seekers.
</P>
<P>
The spending advance reflected a revival in shopping over the
summer and early fall after a temporary spring retreat by
consumers.
</P>
<P>
Disposable personal income -- income after taxes -- also
advanced by 0.4 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
Most of the strength in the personal spending in the month came
from a 0.5 percent increase in services. Spending on nondurable
goods rose 0.3 percent. However, spending on durable goods --
items expected to last for more than three years -- fell by 1.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The fact that disposable income grew more quickly than spending
resulted in an increase in Americans' savings rate. It was up to
3.8 percent in September from 3.6 percent in August and 3.3
percent in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
