<HEADLINE> U.S.: No Dialogue with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
refused to make a dialogue, suggested by Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein, but insisted in its compliance with U.N. weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We're not interested in a dialogue. We're interested in
compliance," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
A three-member U.N. mission is to arrive in Baghdad late on
Tuesday to meet Iraqi officials to resolve dispute over three
American inspectors of U.N. weapons inspection teams, who were
rejected by the Iraqi authorities in entering the country for arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's news agency INA said earlier the U.N. mission was
"supposed to come for a dialogue in order to put things in order."
And the agency reported that Saddam Hussein was calling such a
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said the U.N. mission was not going to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
"The dialogue should consist of spelling out the ways in which
he will comply with the will of the international community as
presented to him by the delegation that will meet with Iraqi
officials," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about possible U.S. unilateral military action, McCurry
said: "I'm not ruling anything in or out."
</P>
<P>
But he described the dispute as "fundamentally a dispute
between the United Nations and Iraq."McCurry declined to specify a
deadline for Saddam to make a favorable response to the U.N.
mission, just talked about the international community "united
against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, Saddam Hussein's repeated defiance of
relevant Security Council resolutions has served to united the
international community and there is a unanimous opinion that
his current action is unacceptable," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
