<HEADLINE> Dow Surges Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average soared Monday to its third-biggest point gain ever,
reflecting a recovery in Asian markets and optimism about the U.S.
economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow jumped 232.31 points to finish at 7,674.39, according
to preliminary numbers. The rebound came just a week after the Dow
plummeted a record 554 points.
</P>
<P>
The Dow is still up nearly 19 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 450 million shares had changed hands by late Monday
afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Helping ease the market tension was a sharp 6 percent gain
Monday on the key Hong Kong stock market and recoveries in other
Asian and European markets as well.
</P>
<P>
A series of economic reports Monday also gave investors more
confidence about the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
Growth in American's personal incomes and spending moderated
and construction spending fell sharply in September, bringing a
robust quarter to a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a private survey by a group of purchasing managers
suggested that manufacturing activity was more hearty than expected
last month.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a nearly 7-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with volume totaling 564.07 million
shares as against 629.05 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list was up 21.49 at 936.11 and
the NYSE composite index was up 11.49 at 492.63.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index was up 36.10 at 1,729.71, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 10.14 at 685.89.
</P>
</TEXT>
