<HEADLINE> Simitis Satisfied with First Day of Balkan Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CRETE, Greece, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis today expressed his satisfaction about the outcome
of the first day of the Balkan summit here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing tonight, Simitis described today's
meeting of the Balkan leaders as "useful and positive".
</P>
<P>
He said that the leaders had discussed their common problems
and bilateral issues among their countries. They had agreed on
settling their problems through systematic cooperation and
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said he had met with four leaders of the Balkan
countries, including Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, to
discuss the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Simitis-Yilmaz meeting this evening was regarded as one of
the most important talks during the summit because the relations
between the two neighbors have witnessed an increased tension in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
Simitis also hailed his talks with Yilmaz as "useful".
</P>
<P>
He said that the two sides had agreed today to continue their
political dialogue in a bid to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz has agreed, according to Simitis, that a third party
such as an international organization might help them to settle
their disputes.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Simitis had accepted the invitation to
visit Turkey, which was extended to him by Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Although Simitis failed to give the date of his visit, analysts
here believe that this marks a breakthrough of the Greek-Turkish
relations because Simitis will be the first Greek premier to visit
Ankara since 1958. 
