<HEADLINE> Chinese President Leaves US for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, winding up a nine-day visit to the United States, left here
by special plane for home this morning.
</P>
<P>
He was given a red-carpet send-off at the Los Angeles
international airport.
</P>
<P>
In a farewell statement, the Chinese leader expressed sincere
thanks, on behalf of his wife and colleagues and in his own name,
to President and Mrs. Clinton, the American government and people
for their warm and grand reception.
</P>
<P>
"During my visit to the United States," the president said, "I
had fruitful talks with President Clinton and met with a broad
spectrum of people. President Clinton and I agreed that China and
the United States should, on the basis of the three China-U.S.
joint communiques, strengthen cooperation and endeavor to build a
constructive strategic partnership oriented towards the 21st
century in the interest of world peace and development. The two
sides also had an in-depth exchange of views and reached broad
agreement on regional and international issues of mutual
interest."
</P>
<P>
"The visit has reached the goal of enhancing mutual
understanding, broadening common ground, developing cooperation
and building a future together," he added.
</P>
<P>
History over the past half century and more has shown that both
China and the United States are two great nations shouldering
major responsibilities for the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite differences in national conditions and other areas, he
said, the two countries share a wide range of significant common
interests in maintaining world peace and stability, promoting
global economic growth and prosperity and protecting the
environment for human survival.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of a long-term, stable and sound
relationship between China and the United States not only serves
the fundamental interests of the two countries but also meets the
common aspirations of the people of the two countries and the rest
of the world," the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
"In the last few days," Jiang said, "I have been impressed by
the warm friendly sentiments of the American people towards the
Chinese people. The time-honored friendship between the people of
China and the United States will serve a powerful driving force
for the development of China-U.S. relations. We have every reason
to be confident about the future China-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
Present at the airport to see President Jiang off were Los
Angeles mayor Richard Riordan, officials from Los Angeles County
and representatives from the local Chinese community. Chinese
Ambassador to the United States Li Daoyu and Counsel General in
Los Angeles Feng Shusen were also present.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's entourage, including his wife Wang Yeping, Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and special assistant Zeng
Qinghong, also left here with the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
