<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Iraq on Consequence of Barring Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States warned on
Monday that Iraq would be greeted with unspecified "firm action" if
it continues to bar American members of the U.N. weapons
inspection teams from entering the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is our view that the Security Council should be prepared to
take firm action to bring about Iraqi compliance in the event they
don't change their mind in the next day or so," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
The stern warning came after Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
refused entry to three American arms inspectors and warned
continued U.S. U-2 reconnaissance flights could be fired on by
Iraqi anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said Rubin's warning was the first time
Washington has placed a time-limit on resolving the dispute
diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States reserved the right to take unilateral
military action against Iraq, but added: "That is not what our
next step is about."
</P>
<P>
A three-member U.N. mission was to arrive in Baghdad last on
Tuesday to meet Iraqi officials to try to resolve the crisis over
the American inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is that if Iraq doesn't change its mind as a result
of this mission and doesn't get the message that this mission is
going to bring, that the Security Council should be prepared to
take firm action," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
