<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iglesias Re-elected to New Term as IDB President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Board of Governors of
the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) unanimously re-elected
Enrique V. Iglesias as Bank President during a special meeting
held here today.
</P>
<P>
Iglesias' new five-year term will begin on April 1, 1998, a
decade after he first became president of the Bank.
</P>
<P>
An IDB news release said that under his leadership, the Bank
has become the premier multilateral lender to Latin America and
the Caribbean. Its authorized subscribed capital was increased
from 34.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1988 to 61 billion dollars in
1989 and to 100 billion dollars in 1994, and lending increased
from 1.68 billion dollars in 1988 to 6.76 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
IDB financing emphasizes poverty reduction, environmental
protection, creation of greater opportunities for youth and women,
rights of indigenous communities, and microenterprise. In recent
years, the Bank diversified its financing to include new areas,
such as judicial reform, social security reform, prevention of
domestic and urban violence, and strengthening of private sector
and democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
Iglesias is a native of Asturias, Spain, and later becomes a
naturalized Uruguayan citizen. He was Uruguay's first Central Bank
president from 1967 to 1969. From 1972 to 1985, Iglesias was
executive secretary of the UN Economic Commission for Latin
America and the Caribbean, based in Santiago, Chile. He was
Uruguay's foreign minister from 1985 to 1988, who presided over
the Uruguay Round of trade negotiations that eventually led to the
creation of the World Trade Organization (WTO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Warns of AIDS Virus Spreading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank report said
today that new evidence shows that while countries in sub-Saharan
Africa have the most people infected with AIDS, the deadly virus
may be on the verge of exploding in Eastern Europe, the former
Soviet Union and other regions.
</P>
<P>
The report said 23 million people are infected with HIV, with
8,500 new cases each day. Approximately 90 percent of all HIV
infections occur in developing countries, where resources to
confront the epidemic are most scarce.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 developing countries have concentrated epidemics,
including Latin America, parts of West Africa and most of
Indochina, the study found.
</P>
<P>
The report said that "for the 2.3 billion people living in
parts of the world where the epidemic is nascent, an early active
government response encouraging safer behavior among those likely
to contract and spread the virus has the potential to avert untold
suffering and save lives."
</P>
<P>
The report recommended that governments act as quickly as
possible with intensive prevention efforts, especially among
people who have many sex partners or inject drugs using
unsterilized needles.
</P>
<P>
Among countries in the early stages of the epidemic are
Bangladesh, the Philippines, most countries of the former Soviet
Union, much of Eastern Europe and parts of China and India, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has committed 632 million U.S. dollars to 61
AIDS prevention projects in 41 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0307 </DOCNO>
