<HEADLINE> Kinkel to Promote Germany's Role as Washington's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel will underscore Germany's role as the main partner of the
United States in Europe during his one-day visit to Washington
Wednesday, said German press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Germany sees itself as the only major European country which is
fully committed to the enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the European Union (EU), the German news
agency DPA quoted German diplomatic sources as saying today.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Washington, Kinkel will meet U.S. President
Bill Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and members of
the U.S. Congress. Major topics for discussions include the
eastward expansion of NATO and the EU, the Middle East peace
process, as well as Western relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
According to German officials, Kinkel is set to tell U.S.
leaders that Europeans will pay their fair share of costs for
taking in new NATO members while warning that disagreement over
the funding issue should not be allowed to weaken the 16-nation
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister is also expected to promote closer
dialogue with Washington on Western relations with Teheran, and
will try to narrow the difference between Bonn and Washington over
the treatment of the Scientology movement in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Before his trip to the United States, Kinkel will visit Canada
Tuesday. 
</P>
