<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Meets Chinese Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu met here today with Wen Jiabao, politburo
member of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party,
to discuss enhancing bilateral economic and trade cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Wen Jiabao expressed satisfaction with the
smooth development of bilateral cooperations in the spheres of
economy, trade and culture, noting that there still exists vast
potential of furthering such cooperations.
</P>
<P>
The two placed special emphasis on the need to boost the
cooperation in the agricultural area. Agriculture plays an
important role in developing China's economy, Netanyahu said,
adding that China, as a big power with 1.2 billion population, is
a huge and attractive market for Israel's advanced agricultural
technologies and expertise.
</P>
<P>
Wen Jiabao, who heads a high-level delegation, said the
relations between China and Israel have been developing smoothly
since the two countries established diplomatic ties in 1992, thus
laying a solid foundation for enhancing cooperation in various
areas, especially in economic, trade and agricultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
He praised the joint Sino-Israeli farm established in Beijing
years ago as a model for furthering bilateral agricultural
cooperation. He also expressed the hope that the agricultural
cooperation would be expanded in the future, especially in areas
of water-saving, irrigation, and farming tools manufacture and
desert-control.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Netanyahu briefed Wen Jiabao on the latest
developments of the Israeli-Palestinian peace process,
reaffirming his intention to accelerate the peace talks to hold
the final-status talks in a bid to reach a package peace deal.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Wen Jiabao reiterated the Chinese position that
the concerned parties in the peace process should settle the
disputes in a cordial way and on the basis of respecting the
related resolutions passed by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He added that China, as a member of the U.N. Security Council,
will continue contributing to achieving a just, comprehensive
and lasting peace in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
