<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroonian President Swears in for Another </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Cameroonian incumbent
President Paul Biya today swore in at the National Assembly for a
new seven-year term after winning re-election in October 12
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Among those present at the inauguration ceremony are
Cameroonian Prime Minister Peter Mafany Musonge, government
officials as well as diplomatic corps.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the swear-in ceremony, Biya pledged to combat
poverty in the country and declared that he will commit himself
to the development of Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his government is determined to enhance
democratic process in the country and uphold national unity.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Cameroon will attach importance to the
development of friendly ties with all nations around the world
and with neighboring countries in particular, while it will
continue to take an active role on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Biya said Cameroon will continue to take belt-tightening
measures it accepted as part of a medium-term accord it signed
with the World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Referring to political turbulence in central Africa, Biya
noted,"there could be no development without security and peace."
He called on Cameroonians to cherish the peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
President Biya, 64, has been in power since 1982. He took over
power from independence President Ahmadou Ahidjo.
</P>
<P>
Biya won 1984 and 1988 elections as sole candidate and 1992
multiparty elections when he narrowly defeated the Social
Democratic Front (SDF) leader John Fru Ndi.
</P>
<P>
The three main opposition political parties which boycotted
the October 12 presidential elections did not attend the
inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The SDF, the National Union for Democracy and Progress (UNDP)
and the Cameroon Democratic Union (CDU) denounced the poll as
rigged from the start. They accused Biya's administration of
rigging all elections since the country embraced multiparty
politics in the early 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
