<HEADLINE> Saddam Discusses with Commanders on US Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
today presided over a meeting of military commanders of the armed
forces amid mounting tensions between Baghdad and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency did not reveal the place and
details of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Saddam and his commanders discussed the
possibility of U.S. military action against Iraq if the present
standoff comes to a showdown.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Saddam convened a special cabinet meeting to study
current political developments and necessary measures to deal
with possible U.S. attacks against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad insisted that it would not reverse its decision to bar
Americans from joining the U.N. weapons inspectors' teams which
are in charge of ensuring the elimination of weapons of mass
destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It has accused the American inspectors of conducting espionage
and obstructing the lifting of strangling U.N. sanctions against
Iraq imposed since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohamed al-Sahhaf issued a statement
Sunday accusing Richard Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraqi mass
destruction weapons, of spreading falsehood.
</P>
<P>
Which law was Butler referring to in claiming that Iraq would
be violating law if it refused to deal with the Americans on the
U.N. commission, he questioned.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Iraq's decision to stop dealing with
American members on the commission, and to demand those in Iraq to
leave the country within a week's time, was a sound and legal
decision.
</P>
<P>
He added that the commission and its inspection teams and
supervision groups could do their work without the participation
of American members.
</P>
<P>
"We are keen to maintain constructive cooperation with the
Special Commission," he said, adding that "non dealing with those
Americans planted in the Special Commission for anti-Iraqi
political ends in no way means non cooperation with the commission."
</P>
</TEXT>
