<HEADLINE> Netanyahu-Clinton Summit Absent From Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The reported summit between
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and American President
Bill Clinton next week was conspicuously absent from Israel's
official agenda announced today.
</P>
<P>
The agenda for Netanyahu's visit to the U.S. next week, which
was announced by the Prime Minister's Office, did not even
include the U.S. capital Washington.
</P>
<P>
This refuted an earlier report broadcasted by Israel Radio
that the Netanyahu-Clinton summit had been nailed.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified official in the Prime Minister's Office was
late quoted by the radio as saying that the U.S. had told Israel
that the summit now depends on the outcome of the current
negotiations held in Washington between Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) deputy head
Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen).
</P>
<P>
The failure of arranging the summit now reflected Clinton's
displeasure with Netanyahu's handling of the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, which was resumed early last month after a
seven-month freeze thanks to the intensive American mediation.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is due to visit the U.S. from November 16 to address
the General Assembly of the Jewish Federations in the U.S. and
Canada, to be held in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
According to the officially announced agenda, Netanyahu will
travel to Britain on November 12 to meet with his British
counterpart Tony Blair before heading to Indianapolis and Los
Angels.
</P>
<P>
For the past month, Israeli officials have been scrambling to
arrange the summit between Netanyahu and Clinton, assuring
Washington that real efforts are being made by the Netanyahu-led
government to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is currently
hosting the Levy-Mazen negotiations in a bid to reach an
agreement on implementing the interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported late last month that Netanyahu was
considering postponing his U.S. trip if Clinton refuses to
receive him, because Clinton's snub would be constructed by
Netanyahu's opponents as evidence that he is out of favor in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
Since Netanyahu came to power in June last year, his hardline
policies have taken the peace process into constant crisis to the
disappointment of the U.S. administration, which has repeatedly
urged for acceleration of the peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
