<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges More AIDS-Prevention Efforts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today called
on developing countries to strengthen their efforts for AIDS
prevention so as to save million of lives and reduce severe
economic and social costs of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
In its latest's report -- Confronting AIDS: Public Priorities
in a Global Epidemic, released here today, the World Bank said
approximately 90 percent of all HIV infections are occurring in
developing countries, countries in sub-Saharan Africa have the
most people infected with AIDS -- 14 million, and the deadly virus
may be on the verge of exploding in Eastern Europe, the former
Soviet Union and other regions.
</P>
<P>
The 353-page report urged governments to act as quickly as
possible with intensive prevention efforts, especially among
people who have many sex partners or inject drugs using
unsterilized needles.
</P>
<P>
The report said that some 23 million people worldwide are now
infected with HIV and that 8,500 people are newly infected each
day. Two decades after the first appearance of the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV), 6 million people have died from
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Confronting AIDS requires that government officials take the
necessary steps to confront the epidemic even when these are
politically controversial," said Joseph Stiglitz, the World Bank's
chief economist and senior vice president who is a former economic
affairs adviser to President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He told the press briefing that the World Bank is one of the
largest sources of money for AIDS prevention, having committed 632
million U.S. dollars to 61 projects in 41 countries.
</P>
<P>
In many countries, government-backed prevention programs do not
reach people with the riskiest behavior, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
However, many countries still have an opportunity to prevent a
widespread HIV epidemic. In 30 developing countries, and in large
areas of China and India, HIV has infected less than 5 percent of
people who engage in very high risk behavior. Bangladesh,
Indonesia, the Philippines, most countries from the former Soviet
Union and much of East Europe are at this early stage of the
epidemic, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the report, more than 40 developing
countries have "concentrated" epidemics, including Pakistan,
Ukraine, most of Latin America, parts of Western Africa, and most
of Indochina. Parts of India and the southwestern regions of China
bordering the "Golden Triangle" of the drug trade also have
concentrated epidemics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, for the 2.3 billion people who live in these
countries and parts of China and India with "nascent" epidemics,
investing in effective prevention now can keep infection rates
very low and at relatively low costs.
</P>
<P>
"HIV moves through populations in a series of overlapping
epidemics," warned Martha Ainsworth, co-author of the report.
"Once the virus has spread widely among people with very risky
behavior, preventing its spread to others becomes increasingly
difficult."
</P>
<P>
In some countries, Ms. Ainsworth said, life expectancy is 10 to
20 years shorter than it would have been in the absence of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Short of an affordable cure, this toll is certain to rise, the
report said. "But the course of the epidemic is not carved in
stone." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Rejects Challenge to California's  Affirmative Action Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Supreme Court
Monday rejected a challenge to California's Proposition 209, which
bans affirmative action -- a formal effort to provide increased
employment and education opportunities for ethnic minorities and
women -- by any level of state or city government.
</P>
<P>
A coalition of civil rights groups had asked the justices to
hear argument on the challenge this term, but the Supreme Court
denied the request Monday without comment.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers following the case anticipate the rejection might open
the floodgates to similar measures across the country, at least on
the county or municipal level. About 26 jurisdictions are
reportedly poised to enact a similar law.
</P>
<P>
California voters passed Proposition 209 -- the California
Civil Rights Initiative -- in November 1996 by 54 to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Proposition 209 says the state "shall not discriminate against,
or grant preferential treatment to, any individual or group on the
basis of race, sex, color, ethnicity or national origin in the
operation of public employment, public education or public
contracting."
</P>
<P>
Earlier the coalition challenged the law, and a federal judge
in San Francisco issued a preliminary injunction against its
implementation, ruling that the state law conflicted with federal
civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
But a federal appeals court panel threw out the injunction, and
refused to block the effects while the challengers took their case
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court last month refused to suspend Proposition
209, but left open the question of whether it would hear argument
in the case until today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
