<HEADLINE> Milosevic: Balkan's Future Relys on Regional Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CRETE, GREECE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia said today that the perspective of the
Balkan nations would depend on accelerated regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the two-day Balkan summit, which opened here today,
Milosevic said the Balkan region was an inevitable part of its
inclusion in the overall European integration processes.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that any autarchy was dangerous not only for social
and economic development, but also peace and stability as a common
goal of the region.
</P>
<P>
"A balanced and comprehensive development of bilateral and
regional cooperation, without any barriers, may ensure a dynamic
development of the region as a whole as well as of each individual
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged European institutions to consider the region as an
integral part of Europe instead of a "permanent hotbed of crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Europe of bloc divisions should not be succeeded by the
Europe of new partitions and discrimination," he said, adding that
it was necessary to narrow the economic gap in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As for the cooperation between the Balkans, Milosevic hoped
that efforts be focused on the strengthening and promotion of
political cooperation by keeping regular contacts and political
dialogue at all levels.
</P>
<P>
He added that efforts should be made for the establishment of a
Balkan free trade zone and the promotion of all-round cooperation,
especially in transport, telecommunications, energy and
environment.
</P>
<P>
On the Bosnian issue, he said that the international community
should not act for them just to arbitrate in disputes between the
parties concerned, but instead create the conditions to help the
legal representatives and entities in fully playing their part.
</P>
</TEXT>
