<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Negotiate for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators started a new round of negotiations on Monday in an
attempt to revive the stalemated peace talks in response to U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's call during her first
visit to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and Palestinian negotiator
Mahmoud Abbas, a senior aide of Chairman Yasser Arafat, met
Albright at the State Department before they began their talks in
a Virginia suburb of Washington.
</P>
<P>
Israel has sent a full negotiation team while the Palestinian
Authority dispatched a few officials for this week's talks as they
did not trust the United States even-handedness in its brokering
for the settlement of disputes between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department, however, tried to persuade the
Palestinian Authority to send more negotiators to Washington so
that the talks could be more effective.
</P>
<P>
Notably absent were some Palestinian experts on what are known
as the interim issues.
</P>
<P>
"They are not here. A significant part of the morning was spent
discussing that without them we won't be able to make any
progress," State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was reported to have said that he sent Abbas to meet
Levy at the Washington talks "only because we received an official
invitation from Madeleine Albright."
</P>
<P>
In the past week, Arafat said he believes the Washington talks
this week are "a waste of time" because of differences over the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The United States said this week's talks have a four-point
agenda: Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation, further Israeli
troops withdrawal from the West Bank, a possible "time-out" on
Jewish settlements, and ways of moving to negotiations on the
final status of Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli government spokesman Moshe Fogel said on Saturday
that the "natural focus" of the talks would be on issues left over
from past agreements, such as creating a Palestinian port and
airport and safe passage between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians said these were limited technical issues that
should be dealt with by joint committees which met last month with
U.S. mediator Dennis Ross present.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want to focus on Israeli redeployment and a
freeze on Jewish settlements before they will consider starting
final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks has been suspended since
March when the Israeli government broke the ground for a Jewish
Housing construction in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German, French, Polish Defense Chiefs Agree on  Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The defense ministers of Germany,
France and Poland today agreed on a three-year program for
military cooperation at the conclusion of a two-day meeting in
east German town of Eufurt.
</P>
<P>
The three countries will hold joint troops exercises and expert
conferences each year during the period, with the presidency
rotating annually between them.
</P>
<P>
Poland is expected to become a full member of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) by April 1999.
</P>
<P>
Last July, the western military alliance invited Poland to
begin talks on NATO membership and the two sides opened formal
discussions in October.
</P>
<P>
French defense chief Alain Richard said the reform of Poland's
armed forces had "progressed very far."
</P>
<P>
German defense chief Volker Ruehe said NATO would allocate one
billion U.S. dollars from its infrastructure fund to help Poland's
integration.
</P>
<P>
Poland was expected to spend over 10 billion dollars in new
weapons technology in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Polish Defense Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz also stressed that
his country hoped for good relations with Russia despite its
efforts to get rid of Russia's geo-political influence.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Onyszkiewicz assured equal partnership with
Germany and France, saying ties with Germany should not be
predominant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
