<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Vows to Strike Hard on Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Interior Minister Hassan
Mohamed el Alfy today announced an all-out campaign to strike hard
on the country's terrorist and criminal elements.
</P>
<P>
"Full planning and preparations are being made by all security
agencies in all the governorates to combat all criminal acts and
to apprehend outlaw elements in the South of Egypt," the minister
said, quoted by the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
During an inspection tour today of Menoufia Governorate, in the
Nile Delta, he told reporters that Egyptian security agencies deal
firmly and decisively with any individual or group's actions which
threaten security.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on the extradition of outlaws, the
minister said there were agreements between Egypt and a number of
world countries to cooperate in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will host a U.N.-sponsored international conference on
combating organized crime and extradition of fugitive terrorists,
Alfy told reporters.
</P>
<P>
A preparatory conference is to be held in the Egyptian northern
coastal city Alexandria next week with the aim of drawing up
proposals on fighting organized crime, he added.
</P>
<P>
Today's visit to Menoufia Governorate is part of a series of
inspection visits of the minister to the various governorates that
have been battered by terrorist attacks in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
According to the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights, armed
Islamist groups bore responsibility for most of the acts of
violence in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Although Muslim militant violence has reportedly declined by
more than 50 percent in during 1995-96, the recent wave of
terrorist attacks around the country has rekindled public fears.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian security services succeeded in reducing the armed
Islamist groups' activities with successive strikes against their
strongholds, resulting in the arrests or deaths of their top
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of Islamic militants executed have
reached 63 since fundamentalists launched a violent
anti-government campaign in March 1992. A total of 2,255 people
have been killed in the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
