<DOCNO> XIE19971104.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VW Posts 83 Percent Surge in Profits Through Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Europe's largest carmaker Volkswagen
today said its net profit reached 852 million marks (492 million U.S.
dollars) in the first nine months of this year, representing an
increase of 83 percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Wolfsburg-based German car giant said its turnover surged by
12.8 percent to 84.01 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
Sales of VW, Audi, Seat (Spain) and Skoda (Czech Republic) cars
reached 3.25 million units during the period, up 8.9 percent,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
VW said its car sales in Germany were up 2.9 percent to 763,000,
compared with the sales abroad of 2.49 million cars, an increase of
about 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the nine-month period, the production of VW-brand cars totaled
almost 2.99 million, up 5.8 percent, while Skoda output surged 28.7
percent to 243,500 cars, Audi output rose 14 percent to 412,000 and
Seat output rose 13.5 percent to 299,000.
</P>
<P>
VW also said that it expected the daily output of its new "Golf-IV
car to reach 3,300 units by mid-1998, compared with the current output
of 1,000 per day. VW's sales target for the Golf in 1998 is 700,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
